preds: The pathology report indicates that the vaginal-cervical biopsy reveals moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. In contrast, the bladder biopsy shows marked chronic inflammation with reactive epithelial atypia, but no carcinoma is identified. The patient is a female with a history of squamous cell carcinoma of unknown primary origin.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of bilateral, multifocal prostate adenocarcinoma following a radical prostatectomy, with the index tumor located in the left mid/base and classified as Gleason pattern 4+5=9. There is evidence of extraprostatic extension at the left base (up to 7 mm), right apex (5 mm), and left apex (1 mm), with positive pathological margins at the right apex (2 mm) and left apex (0.5 mm). Additionally, separate multifocal transition zone adenocarcinoma is present, with no lymphovascular invasion identified and clear seminal vesicles.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade leiomyosarcoma with pleomorphic features from a right shoulder soft tissue mass. The tumor measures 3.8 cm and shows positive staining for actin (SMA) and Ki-67, with negative results for desmin, S100, and CD34. Margins are negative for sarcoma, and necrosis is present in 5% of the tumor.

The pathology report indicates that the left frontal brain tumor biopsy is diagnosed as an oligoastrocytoma (WHO Grade II), confirming a low-grade glioma with rare mitotic figures and no vascular proliferation. Genetic analysis shows allelic loss on chromosome arms 1p and 19q, which is typical for oligodendrogliomas, and no evidence of methylated MGMT promoter was detected. The tumor cells exhibit diffuse p53 positivity and a Ki-67 labeling index of approximately 4 to 5%.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a diagnosis of prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3+4=7, involving both lobes of the prostate and a maximum tumor diameter of 2.2 cm, but confined to the prostate without evidence of extraprostatic extension or lymph node involvement. All examined surgical margins are free of neoplasia, and multifocal high-grade prostate intraepithelial neoplasia is present. The final TNM pathologic stage is pT2c, N0, Mx, indicating localized disease without lymphatic or distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that the left chest wall mass is a malignant spindle cell neoplasm consistent with a malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor. Microscopic examination reveals a spindle cell neoplasm with variable cellularity, arranged in storiform or fascicular patterns, and shows focal invasion into skeletal muscle and adipose tissue. The tumor cells are positive for vimentin and CD57, and the patient's clinical history suggests neurofibromatosis, correlating with the findings of numerous small cutaneous nodules along the thorax.

The pathology report indicates that all three left sentinel lymph nodes biopsied are negative for tumor, confirming no lymph node involvement. A segmental mastectomy revealed a 1.0 cm infiltrating duct carcinoma with a Nottingham score of 6, characterized by no lymphovascular invasion and a small component of ductal carcinoma in situ. The tumor is hormone receptor positive (estrogen and progesterone) and HER-2/neu negative, with negative surgical margins and additional findings of benign fibrocystic changes and a fibroadenoma.

The pathology report indicates a renal tumor measuring 5x4x4 cm, located at a pole of the kidney, characterized as a moderately-margin, soft, solid mass with a yellow-gray appearance. Microscopic examination reveals high-density tumor tissue composed of elongated tubules or papillary structures, lined by moderately stratified cylindrical or cuboidal cells with irregular, hyperchromatic nuclei and prominent nucleoli, indicating a diagnosis of papillary renal cell carcinoma, moderately differentiated. The tumor is confined to the kidney, with no specified details on lymphatic or venous invasion, and no evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment noted.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of grade 1 papillary renal cell carcinoma, measuring 4 cm, located in the upper pole of the left kidney, with no evidence of tumor necrosis, sarcomatoid features, or lymph-vascular invasion. The tumor is confined to the kidney with negative surgical margins and no extension into surrounding tissues or lymph nodes. Additionally, there is a 2 cm unilocular renal cyst adjacent to the carcinoma, and the non-neoplastic kidney shows signs of atherosclerosis and minimal interstitial fibrosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.0 cm, with the tumor extending up to but not through the pleura. The frozen section diagnosis of large cell carcinoma was confirmed, and the margins are reported as free of tumor. No lymph nodes were resected during the procedure, and areas of dense fibrosis were noted in association with the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive lobular carcinoma in the right breast, measuring 2.2 cm, with extensive lobular carcinoma in situ (LCIS) also identified. Of the two sentinel lymph nodes examined, one showed rare cytokeratin-positive cells, while the other was benign, indicating no significant metastatic involvement. Surgical margins were negative for invasive carcinoma, although LCIS was present in the medial, superior, inferior, and lateral margins.

The pathology report indicates that the patient, a male with a diagnosis of invasive well-differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma of the left mandible, has a tumor measuring 4.2 cm that invades the mandibular bone and shows perineural invasion, with a microscopic focus of carcinoma at the posterior bony margin. All examined lymph nodes from both sides of the neck (totaling 53) are negative for carcinoma, and additional margins and biopsies from surrounding tissues also show no evidence of malignancy. Immunohistochemical analysis reveals strong positivity for EGFR, and HPV studies are pending.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme, WHO grade IV, in multiple biopsies from the right temporal region, with varying degrees of tumor necrosis and cellularity. Immunohistochemical analysis shows a high percentage of tumor cells expressing MGMT, which may suggest a diminished response to certain therapies, while retained expression of PTEN could indicate a more favorable prognosis. Additionally, the fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) analysis revealed a normal EGFR signal pattern, suggesting no aberrant EGFR amplification in the tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in the cervix, measuring 7.0 cm, with a maximum invasion depth of 7 mm and focal lymphovascular space invasion. Metastatic carcinoma was found in 2 out of 7 right obturator lymph nodes, with focal extracapsular extension, while the left obturator lymph nodes were free of carcinoma. An intact female fetus, estimated to be 18 to 19 weeks gestational age, was present with no congenital anomalies or histopathological abnormalities identified.

The pathology report indicates a 16-cm large bowel resection specimen containing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colorectal type, which has infiltrated the pericolic fatty tissue and metastasized to three regional lymph nodes. Both the large bowel and mesenteric resection margins are tumor-free. Additionally, there is an inflammatory portion of the urinary bladder fused with the large bowel and ductus deferens in the tumor area, with the tumor staged as pT3 pN1 (3/43) pMX; G2, LO V0, local R0.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of carcinosarcoma (malignant mullerian mixed tumor) of the endometrium with myometrial invasion measuring 8 mm and lymphovascular invasion identified. All examined sentinel lymph nodes and additional lymph nodes, as well as the omentum, were found to be benign with no evidence of metastatic tumor. The tumor exhibits a high proliferative index, but there is no immunohistochemical support for neuroendocrine differentiation.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive ductal adenocarcinoma in the left breast, with a tumor size of 2.3 x 2.1 x 1.2 cm and associated lymphatic/vascular invasion. Sentinel lymph node biopsies revealed metastatic adenocarcinoma in both sentinel nodes, with micrometastases detected in one node and a larger metastasis of 6 mm in the other. The surgical margins are negative, and additional tests for hormone receptors and other markers are pending.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an oligoastrocytoma, predominantly oligodendroglioma, classified as low grade (WHO grade II). The MIB-1 labeling index is 5.0%, reflecting an intermediate level of proliferative activity consistent with low-grade histologic features. Microscopic examination reveals a mildly to moderately hypercellular glial neoplasm with a predominance of microgemistocyte cells, and no evidence of mitotic figures, microvascular proliferation, or necrosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of classical seminoma in the right testicle, measuring 1.5 cm, which is confined to the testis and invades the tunica albuginea and rete testis, but shows no involvement of the tunica vaginalis or lymphovascular invasion. The spermatic cord and its margin are free of tumor. The specimen was obtained from a 31-year-old man who underwent a right radical orchiectomy due to a right testicular mass.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated ductal breast carcinoma with invasive growth, identified during a left mastectomy preparation. The tumor has a dorsal margin of less than 0.1 cm, while the ventral margin is 0.5 cm, and other resection margins are greater than 1 cm. Additionally, all eleven examined lymph nodes are carcinoma-free, suggesting no lymphatic spread of the disease.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme in the left temporal region of the brain, confirmed through both frozen section and excision specimens. Microscopic examination reveals extensive infiltration by neoplastic glial cells, with notable pleomorphism, mitotic activity, and areas of necrosis. The MIB-1 proliferation index is reported at 9%, suggesting a moderate level of cellular proliferation within the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a right renal mass diagnosed as a renal oncocytic neoplasm measuring 12 cm, which is confined to the renal parenchyma with free vascular and ureteral margins, and no tumor detected in the adrenal gland or lymph nodes. Immunohistochemical staining suggests the tumor has low malignant potential, with differential diagnoses including low-grade chromophobe carcinoma and atypical oncocytoma. Cytogenetic analysis shows a normal male karyotype, which may indicate an overgrowth of normal tissue rather than a malignant tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in multiple locations, including the omentum, ovaries, and fallopian tubes, with significant tumor involvement in the omentum and surface adhesions. The uterus shows foci of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the endometrium, but the lower uterine segment and cervix are free of carcinoma, and leiomyomas are noted in the myometrium. The findings suggest a complex scenario of synchronous primary peritoneal and endometrial carcinomas or potential metastasis from the peritoneum, given the extensive tumor spread and the patient's history of endometrial adenocarcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme, grade IV, in a biopsy, tumor resection, and tumor aspiration from the left anterior temporal region of the brain. The tumor exhibits heterogeneous histological features, including highly cellular areas with pleomorphic nuclei, microvascular proliferation, necrosis, and abundant mitoses, with positive immunohistochemistry for GFAP in many neoplastic astrocytes. The clinical history notes the patient presented with a left anterior temporal ring-enhancing lesion, and the final diagnosis was confirmed by the attending pathologist after reviewing all pathology slides.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive lobular carcinoma of the left breast, with a tumor size of 2.7 x 1.4 x 2.8 cm and metastases found in axillary lymph nodes (No IX/XI). Immunohistochemical examination shows over 75% positivity for estrogen and progesterone receptors, while HER2 gene amplification was not found. The tumor is classified as NHG2, pTIc, pN2a, indicating a moderate grade of malignancy and the presence of cancer spread to lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates the presence of acinar adenocarcinoma of the prostate with a Gleason score of 8 (4+4) and a tertiary pattern of 3, with 30% of the prostate involved by carcinoma. Seminal vesicle invasion and lymphovascular invasion are present, while surgical margins are free of invasive carcinoma. Lymph node involvement is noted with one metastasis in the right external iliac lymph nodes and one each in the right and left paravesical lymph nodes, leading to a pathological staging of pT3b, pN1, pMX.

The final diagnosis for the left frontal tumor is oligodendroglioma (WHO Grade II), with further analysis for allelic loss on chromosomes 1p and 19q pending. The fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) results indicate that both chromosome 1p and 19q are intact, showing no evidence of allelic loss, which is associated with chemoresponsiveness and longer progression-free survival in gliomas. The tumor was assessed through biopsy and excision, with multiple tissue fragments submitted for analysis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the uterus, with a histologic grade of 2/3 and a maximum tumor size of 4.8 cm, showing myometrial invasion of 0.5 cm. The cervix is involved at the upper portion of the endocervical glands, but no lymphovascular invasion is identified, and all examined pelvic lymph nodes are negative for malignancy. The overall AJCC pathologic stage is classified as pT1a, pNo, indicating early-stage endometrial cancer.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive adenocarcinoma of the transverse colon, classified as moderately differentiated (grade 2 of 4), with a depth of invasion through the muscularis propria into the subserosa and pericolic soft tissue. All surgical margins are negative for cancer, with no lymphovascular or perineural invasion identified, and no metastasis found in the 25 examined regional lymph nodes. Immunohistochemical staining shows normal expression for microsatellite instability markers, suggesting the absence of hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC), and the tumor is staged as pT3 pNO according to AJCC guidelines.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 5.5 cm located in the cecum, with invasion through the muscularis propria into subserosal adipose tissue. All examined margins and 25 pericolonic lymph nodes are free of carcinoma, with no evidence of angiolymphatic or perineural invasion. The tumor is staged as pT3a, N0, MX, and the terminal ileum and appendix show no significant abnormalities.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma (cholangiocarcinoma) in the gallbladder, measuring 3.8 cm, with invasion into the muscle layer but free margins from invasive carcinoma. Additionally, there is evidence of chronic cholecystitis and cholelithiasis with a perforation, but no tumor was found at the perforation site. The portal tissue resection showed non-specific inflammation without any neoplasia.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of unifocal papillary carcinoma in the left lobe of the thyroid, with a tumor size of 2.5 cm. The tumor is classified as pT2, meaning it is greater than 2 cm but less than 4 cm and is confined to the thyroid, with uninvolved margins and no evidence of vascular or lymphatic invasion. Regional lymph nodes and distant metastasis could not be assessed as none were submitted for examination.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lung, with a tumor measuring 70 mm and significant lymphatic permeation but no blood vessel or perineural invasion. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is identified in the hilar, subcarinal, and upper medial sternal lymph nodes, with all lymph node cross-sections showing tumor involvement. The tumor is very close to the hilar soft tissue margin, and the overall classification is T4N2M1, indicating advanced disease.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a poorly cellular fibrous tissue with no neoplasm identified in one specimen, while multiple other specimens reveal a mildly to modestly hypercellular glial neoplasm that diffusely infiltrates both gray and white matter, consistent with anaplastic oligoastrocytoma. The report notes the absence of mitotic figures and highlights areas of dystrophic calcifications, edema, and chronic inflammation in the surrounding tissue. An addendum suggests anaplastic progression of a low-grade glioma based on varying MIB-1 reactivity within the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the sigmoid colon, classified as G2, with erosions on the tumor surface and chronic inflammation surrounding the tumor. The cancer has infiltrated the parietal layers of the sigmoid colon, reaching the outer layers of the tunica muscularis, but there is no evidence of metastasis in the examined lymph nodes (0/12) or at the resection margins. The tumor is staged as pT2, pNo, MX, R0, indicating localized disease without lymph node involvement or metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast, with a tumor size of 3.1 x 1.5 x 1.7 cm and evidence of metastasis in the axillary lymph nodes. Immunohistochemical analysis shows estrogen receptors in 75% and progesterone receptors in 10% of neoplastic cells, with a positive HER2 score of 3+. The histopathological classification is NHG3, with a pT2 and pN1a staging.

The pathology report confirms a diagnosis of left breast cancer following a left segmental mastectomy and axillary dissection. The tumors are identified as infiltrating multifocal poorly differentiated duct carcinoma, with estrogen receptor positivity at 90% and progesterone receptor positivity at 60%, while HER-2/NEU is negative. Additionally, eleven lymph nodes from the left axilla were examined and found to be negative for metastatic carcinoma, although lymphovascular permeation was noted in the breast tissue.

The pathology report indicates a gastrectomy specimen with a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 10.0 x 11.0 x 1.5 cm, which has invaded the serosa. Details regarding lymph nodes, margins, and invasion characteristics are not specified. No additional pathologic findings or comments were provided in the report.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade serous adenocarcinoma of the endometrium, with tumor invasion measuring 21 mm into the myometrium and extending into the lower uterine segment and cervix, accompanied by extensive lymphovascular invasion. Additional findings include an 8 mm endometrial polyp, focal adenomyosis, and multiple leiomyomata, with the largest measuring 11 cm. The overall pathologic stage is classified as T3a/NX/M1 (Stage IVB), indicating distant metastasis, particularly to the omentum.

The pathology report indicates that a left adrenalectomy was performed, revealing a tumor weighing 96 grams and measuring 6.7 x 4.6 cm. The diagnosis is adrenal cortical carcinoma, characterized by a Weiss score of 7. This score suggests a high-grade malignancy with aggressive features.

The pathology report indicates that eight benign lymph nodes were identified in the subcarinal region, and a lobectomy of the right lower lung lobe revealed a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.4 cm with visceral pleura invasion. All surgical margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being less than 1 mm from the tumor. Additionally, two benign lymph nodes were found in the inferior pulmonary region and four in the lower paratracheal area, with no evidence of lymph-vascular invasion or distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a choroidal melanoma of the epithelioid cell type in the enucleated right eye, with a tumor size of 15mm x 12mm and associated retinal detachment. Histological examination reveals a bilobed melanoma arising from the ciliary muscle, with necrosis and a predominance of epithelioid cells, but no evidence of scleral invasion or extraocular growth. Molecular genetic analysis shows monosomy 3 and gains in chromosome 8, placing the patient in a high-risk group for metastatic melanoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of anaplastic oligodendroglioma, grade III, located in the left frontal mass, characterized by early microvascular proliferation, high cellularity, and brisk mitotic activity. The specimen consists of cerebral cortex and underlying white matter, with notable gray discoloration and loss of demarcation at the gray-white junction. Additionally, fluorescence in situ hybridization revealed loss of chromosomal arms 1p and 19q, which may suggest a more favorable response to adjuvant therapy.

The pathology report indicates the presence of hepatocellular carcinoma in the left lobe of the liver, characterized as moderately differentiated with vascular invasion and extension to the surgical margins. An abdominal nodule was found to be benign, showing fat necrosis and fibrosis, while the gallbladder exhibited mild chronic cholecystitis and cholelithiasis without evidence of malignancy. Additional liver biopsies confirmed the diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma, with no signs of melanoma or adrenal cortical carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade III, with a tumor size of 2.7 x 2.7 x 1.5 cm, classified as AJCC pT2. The surgical margins are negative for tumor, with the closest margin being 1.5 cm away from the tumor. Additionally, two left axillary sentinel lymph nodes are negative for tumor involvement, confirming the absence of metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that the anterior prostatic fat and left anterior apex biopsies show benign fibroadipose tissue and skeletal muscle with no evidence of prostate or tumor. The radical prostatectomy revealed prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 5+4=9, confined to the prostate, along with extensive high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia (HGPIN), but no tumor was found in the seminal vesicles or lymph nodes. Additionally, there is evidence of lymphatic space invasion, but no extraprostatic extension, leading to a final staging of pT2cN0L1.

The pathology report indicates that a female patient with a history of toxic goiter underwent a total thyroidectomy, revealing a tall cell variant of papillary carcinoma that spans the entire thyroid and measures at least 7 cm, with extensive extrathyroidal extension into surrounding tissues. Additionally, metastatic papillary thyroid carcinoma was found in all examined lymph nodes, including the delphian and left paratracheal nodes, with no extranodal extension identified. The report also notes benign findings in the pretracheal and left supramediastinal tissues, with one parathyroid gland involved by the carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder specimen shows chronic cholecystitis and cholelithiasis, while the liver specimen reveals moderately differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma (grade II/III) measuring 12 x 9 x 2 cm, with invasion into peri-hepatic adipose tissue and peritumoral intravascular invasion. Two satellite nodules were identified, and tumor cells were present at the resection margin, which is 1 mm from the nearest nodule. The background liver tissue is noted to be cirrhotic, with significant inflammation characterized by plasma cells and eosinophils.

The pathology report indicates that the right leg mass is diagnosed as a high-grade undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma, measuring 8 x 6 x 3 cm, with 20% necrosis and evidence of vascular invasion. Immunohistochemical staining shows the tumor is negative for melanoma markers and other specific lineages, supporting the classification as undifferentiated sarcoma. The surgical margins are negative, with the closest margin being 1 mm from the tumor, and the specimen includes a superficial ulcer on the skin.

The pathology report indicates the presence of two foci of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast, with the dominant mass measuring 1.9 cm and a satellite focus of 0.6 cm, both showing no lymphovascular invasion. The tumor is classified as Nottingham grade 2, with a cribriform type ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) constituting 10% of the total tumor volume, and one sentinel lymph node is positive for metastatic tumor with focal extracapsular extension. Estrogen and progesterone receptors are positive, while HER2 is negative, and surgical margins are focally involved by the invasive component.

The pathology report confirms a diagnosis of infiltrative duct carcinoma in the left breast, measuring 2.4 cm, with a Bloom-Richardson grade of III. All surgical margins are free of tumor, with the closest margin being 0.2 cm from the tumor, and sentinel lymph nodes are negative for malignancy. The overall classification is PTNM T2, N0, MX, indicating stage IIA breast cancer.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of primary endometrial cancer, specifically FIGO grade 3 endometrioid adenocarcinoma with squamous differentiation, showing 20% myometrial invasion and no serosal, cervical, or adnexal involvement. The tumor is estrogen receptor positive and progesterone receptor negative, with lymphovascular space invasion present but no regional lymph node involvement detected in the examined samples. Additional findings include extensive adenomyosis, and the overall AJCC pathologic stage is classified as pT1a pN0, corresponding to FIGO stage IA.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade poorly differentiated endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium, involving approximately 50% of the endometrial surface and invading about 35% of the myometrium, classified as FIGO stage 1A. There is evidence of focal lymphovascular invasion, but all examined lymph nodes (32 in total) are negative for tumor involvement. Additional findings include atypical hyperplasia, endometrial polyps, adenomyosis, and chronic cervicitis, with immunohistochemical staining suggesting a more aggressive tumor profile.

The pathology report indicates that the right lower lobe of the lung contains a moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma measuring 62 mm, with visceral pleural invasion and satellite tumor nodules present. One of three peribronchial lymph nodes shows metastatic carcinoma, while two others are negative for malignancy. The bronchial margin is clear of tumor, and the overall pathologic stage is classified as IIIA.

The lung biopsy reveals an infiltrating epithelioid neoplasm consistent with malignant mesothelioma. The tumor cells are positive for broad spectrum keratin, calretinin, and WT-1, while TTF-1 and CEA are negative. The findings suggest a diagnosis of malignant mesothelioma, epithelioid type.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of carcinomasarcoma of the endometrium (malignant mixed MÃ¼llerian tumor) following a total hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, with no myometrial or endocervical invasion and no definite vascular invasion identified. All examined lymph nodes from various regions (right and left para-aortic, external iliac, and obturator) were reported as benign, and the omentum was negative for tumor. Immunohistochemical analysis showed no support for heterologous rhabdomyoblastic differentiation in the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a subtotal gastrectomy specimen revealing a moderately differentiated intestinal type adenocarcinoma measuring 3 cm, which invades the muscularis propria but has free surgical margins. No malignancy was identified in the three examined regional lymph nodes, and there is a suspicious area in the periserosal adipose tissue, although no additional gross lymph nodes were found. The tumor is staged as pT2 with no evidence of distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of pheochromocytoma from a specimen labeled "interaortocaval tumor," measuring 5.5 x 4 x 3.5 cm, with surgical margins free of tumor. One lymph node was examined, and no tumor was identified, while no adrenal tissue was found in the specimen. The tumor was described as a single piece of soft, red/purple tissue with a homogeneous, dark purple cut surface.

The pathology report indicates that the specimen from the right frontal region of the brain is diagnosed as an anaplastic oligodendroglioma (WHO Grade III), characterized by areas of increased cellularity and mitotic activity. The frozen section analysis revealed extensive low-grade oligodendroglioma features, with a Ki-67 labeling index of 7-12%, and FISH analysis confirmed deletions of chromosomes 1p and 19q. These genetic alterations are associated with a potentially better prognosis and response to chemotherapy in oligodendroglial tumors.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has invasive high-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma, with a significant tumor mass found in the bladder and involvement of left pelvic lymph nodes. Specifically, one of the left pelvic lymph nodes and three out of sixteen left pelvic lymph nodes were positive for metastatic urothelial carcinoma, while the right pelvic lymph nodes were benign. The tumor has invaded extravesicular soft tissue, and all surgical margins, including ureteral and distal urethral margins, are negative for tumor involvement.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade serous carcinoma, oxyphilic variant, in the left ovary, measuring 16.5 cm, with benign follicle cysts present and no significant abnormalities in the left fallopian tube. All examined lymph nodes (34 total) and other tissues, including the omentum and appendix, showed no evidence of tumor, while peritoneal cytology was malignant. The tumor is classified as FIGO stage IC due to microscopic tumor growth to the inked surface of the ovary, with a high serum CA125 level noted.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has been diagnosed with glioblastoma, a high-grade astrocytic neoplasm, following excisional biopsies of brain tumors from the right temporal region. The tumor exhibits characteristics such as nuclear anaplasia, frequent mitoses, and a high MIB-1 proliferation index of 28%, suggesting aggressive behavior. Immunohistochemical analysis shows overexpression of the p53 protein and an infiltrative nature of the neoplasm, confirming the diagnosis of glioblastoma (WHO grade IV).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 7 (3+4), which is confined to the prostate and involves both the right and left lobes, affecting less than 10% of the prostatic tissue. There is no involvement of surgical margins, seminal vesicles, or lymph nodes, and the pathological staging is classified as pT2c. Additionally, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) is noted as an incidental finding.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a low-grade papillary renal cell carcinoma in the left renal mass, which was confirmed through microscopic examination and immunohistochemical staining. The tumor measures approximately 2.7 cm and exhibits a unifocal growth pattern without evidence of necrosis or vascular invasion. The surgical procedure performed was a robotically-assisted laparoscopic left partial nephrectomy, and the margins and extent of invasion could not be accurately assessed due to the specimen's morcellated state.

The histopathological examination of the left breast and axillary tissues revealed a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma. Immunohistochemical analysis showed that estrogen receptors were present in less than 10% of the neoplastic cell nuclei, with no progesterone receptors detected. Additionally, the HER2 protein exhibited a positive reaction in the invasive cancerous cells, scoring 3+.

The pathology report indicates that the left breast wide local excision revealed usual ductal hyperplasia without atypia and no tumor, while the right breast mastectomy showed multifocal invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 10 cm, with the tumor extending close to the deep surgical margin. Sentinel lymph nodes #2 and #3, as well as an additional sentinel lymph node from the right axilla, were positive for metastatic carcinoma, while sentinel lymph node #1 and the majority of lymph nodes from the right axillary contents were negative for metastases. The tumor is classified as invasive lobular carcinoma, ER positive, PR negative, and HER2 negative, with a pathological staging of pT3N2a.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of right renal cell carcinoma, specifically the eosinophilic variant of chromophobe carcinoma, with a histologic grade of 3 and a tumor size of 8.7 cm. The tumor has invaded the renal sinus adipose tissue but shows no capsular invasion or involvement of major veins, ureter, or lymph nodes, with surgical margins remaining uninvolved. The report highlights that the initial core biopsy was misinterpreted as renal oncocytoma, but the excision specimen confirms the diagnosis of chromophobe carcinoma based on immunostaining results.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma, usual variant, measuring 2.4 cm, with unifocal involvement in the right lobe and positive surgical margins at the posterior margin. There is no lymphovascular invasion identified, but blood vascular invasion is present, and the thyroid gland shows severe lymphocytic thyroiditis. Additionally, five lymph nodes from a regional dissection are negative for metastatic carcinoma, confirming no spread to these nodes.

The pathology report describes a 4x4x1 cm ulcerated mass in the left heel skin, diagnosed as poorly differentiated malignant melanoma. Microscopic examination reveals necrotic and hyperplastic epidermis with spindle or oval tumor cells containing melanin, and the tumor has invaded the dermis and fat tissue. Additionally, one out of two examined lymph nodes shows metastasis, and the Breslow tumor thickness at diagnosis is 8 mm.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of conventional clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, with a tumor size of 9 cm and evidence of renal vein invasion, classified as pT3b. The surgical margins are free of tumor, and there is chronic interstitial inflammation in the non-neoplastic kidney tissue, while the adrenal gland and lymph nodes are not involved. Additionally, the excised falciform ligament shows benign fibro-adipose tissue with no tumor present.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder shows no pathological diagnosis, while the liver exhibits chronic hepatitis B with mild activity and severe fibrosis (Stage 3). Additionally, a moderately differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma measuring 3.0 cm was identified in the liver and has been completely excised, with no evidence of endothelial-tined space invasion. The liver mass is located close to the resection margin, but the remainder of the liver parenchyma appears grossly unremarkable.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.0 cm, located in the cecum/ascending colon, with evidence of invasion through the muscularis propria into pericolonic adipose tissue. The tumor has negative proximal, distal, and radial resection margins, and no lymphovascular, venous, or perineural invasion is identified, although there is a suspicious focus of extramural venous invasion noted in an addendum. Additionally, there is one separate adenoma present, and the regional lymph nodes show no evidence of metastasis (0/30).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma from a biopsy of the right occipital lobe, with a MIB-1 labeling index of approximately 20%. The gross examination revealed multiple tissue fragments measuring 0.8 to 0.6 cm, and microscopic analysis showed characteristics typical of a high-grade glioma, including hypercellularity, pleomorphism, mitotic figures, vascular hyperplasia, and significant necrosis. The intraoperative consultation confirmed the presence of a glioma.

The pathology report indicates the presence of moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma on the dorsum of the tongue, with a maximum tumor diameter of 3.4 cm and positive perineural invasion, while the posterior and deep margins are positive for tumor. All examined lymph nodes from both the right and left neck are negative for tumor, indicating no regional metastasis. Other specimens from the tongue margins show chronic inflammation and reactive changes but are negative for high-grade dysplasia or carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that the specimen is from a male patient with a tumor located in the right frontal region. The diagnosis is an oligodendroglioma, classified as grade II according to the World Health Organization (WHO) grading system. This suggests a low-grade glioma with a relatively favorable prognosis compared to higher-grade tumors.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of stomach adenocarcinoma (G3, pT2, pNO) following a total organ resection due to suspicion of cancer of the cardia. The tumor, measuring 12.8 x 11.7 x 2.9 cm, infiltrated the entire thickness of the stomach wall and surrounding fat tissue, but the excision margins, omentum, and lymph nodes were free of neoplastic lesions. Additionally, the spleen and pancreas were also found to be free of cancer.

The pathology report indicates a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the right upper lobe, measuring approximately 47 mm, with evidence of blood vessel invasion but no lymphatic or perineural invasion. There is no convincing pleural invasion, and the bronchial resection margins are clear, although squamous metaplasia with severe dysplasia is noted at the right middle lobe bronchial margin. Additionally, all examined lymph nodes show only reactive changes with no evidence of malignancy, resulting in a classification of T2N0MX for the tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a 15.3 cm leiomyosarcoma in the small bowel mesentery, with clear margins. Additionally, the hysterectomy specimen shows leiomyomas, endometrial polyps, and proliferative phase endometrium, while the ovaries and fallopian tubes on the right side show no diagnostic abnormalities. The microscopic examination of the leiomyosarcoma reveals pleomorphic spindled cells with significant pleomorphism and foci of necrosis, but no vascular invasion was noted.

The pathology report indicates that a total thyroidectomy was performed, revealing a 1.0 cm papillary carcinoma of the thyroid, follicular variant, with two out of eight paratracheal lymph nodes positive for metastatic carcinoma. The pretracheal and right paratracheal lymph nodes were both benign, and the resection margins were negative for carcinoma. Additional findings included chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis, and the overall pathologic stage was classified as pT1, N1a, Mx.

The pathology report indicates that there is no tumor present in the periprostatic lymph nodes, anterior apex, or both left and right pelvic lymph nodes. However, the prostate contains a single focus of prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 9 (4 + 5), located primarily in the anterior half of the prostate, with a potential focal extension to the left apical margin. The seminal vesicles and segments of the vasa deferentia are free of tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of carcinosarcoma (malignant Mullerian mixed tumor) of the endometrium with heterologous differentiation, showing myometrial invasion of less than 50% and tumor nodules on the uterine serosa. Metastatic carcinosarcoma was identified in the omental nodule, cul-de-sac, rectal implant, and periureteral tissue, while multiple lymph nodes and other specimens were found to be benign. The left ovary contained a mucinous cystadenoma, and additional testing on the left sentinel common iliac lymph node revealed no evidence of metastatic tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a B3 thymoma, characterized by a primary mass measuring 32x14 mm and multiple distinct nodules, with the largest infiltrating adjacent mediastinal tissue. The neoplasm is partially encapsulated, and additional small thymoma nodules were identified, with no invasive tendency noted. Reactive lymph nodes were found in the surrounding adipose tissue, and the overall diagnosis is classified as Stage IIA according to the Masaoka-Koga system.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a right renal cell carcinoma of the clear cell type, with a nuclear grade of II/IV, measuring 6.5 cm and confined within the renal capsule without invasion of the renal vein or involvement of surgical margins. The right hilar lymph nodes and the fat at the lower pole of the kidney are benign, while the biopsy of the right 11th rib is pending further evaluation due to the need for decalcification. Overall, the findings suggest localized renal cancer with no evidence of metastasis in the examined lymph nodes or surrounding tissues.

The pathology report indicates that the distal pancreas contains an invasive poorly differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma measuring 2.8 cm, with negative resection margins and evidence of lymphovascular and perineural invasion, while all examined lymph nodes are negative for malignancy. The spleen appears normal, and an accessory splenule is noted, while the gallbladder shows signs of cholelithiasis and intestinal metaplasia without dysplasia. Overall, the findings suggest a significant pancreatic malignancy with no metastatic spread to lymph nodes or the spleen.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a right breast simple mastectomy and sentinel lymph node biopsy due to a diagnosis of invasive breast cancer. The findings reveal multicentric intralobular and infiltrating lobular carcinoma, with the largest invasive tumor measuring 3.5 cm, and metastatic carcinoma identified in one of the sentinel lymph nodes, while other lymph nodes showed no evidence of malignancy. The surgical margins and nipple skin are free of tumor, and there is no evidence of lymphovascular invasion.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has high-grade urothelial carcinoma with squamous differentiation in the bladder, which is invasive into the outer half of the muscularis propria, measuring 3.2 x 2.3 x 1.3 cm. All examined lymph nodes (25 total) from both left and right pelvic dissections show no evidence of tumor (0/25). Resection margins, including those of the ureters and soft tissue, are negative for tumor presence, indicating no residual disease at the surgical margins.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrioid adenocarcinoma (FIGO grade 3) in the uterus, with a tumor size of 3.1 x 2.1 x 1.1 cm and superficial invasion into the myometrium. Both left and right pelvic lymph node dissections revealed no evidence of malignancy, with a total of 33 lymph nodes examined (0/21 from the left and 0/12 from the right). The remaining findings include benign leiomyomata and a benign fibroma in the left ovary, with negative margins and no tumor involvement in the cervix or fallopian tubes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of locally advanced, poorly differentiated, nonkeratinizing squamous cell carcinoma of the left upper lobe of the lung, classified as pT4 pN1 V1 RX(R1?), stage III. The tumor exhibits endobronchial growth and has metastasized to local bronchopulmonary lymph nodes, with invasion into the mediastinum but not infiltrating the resected pericardial layer. Additional findings include tumor necroses, fresh hemorrhagic pulmonary infarction, and moderate anthracotic pigment deposits in the lung parenchyma and lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast, with the tumor measuring 2.8 cm and extending to within 1 cm of the deep margin. The modified radical mastectomy specimen also revealed metastases in 6 out of 23 examined axillary lymph nodes, classified as pN2a. Additional immunohistochemical stains for hormone receptors and HER2 are pending for further evaluation.

The histopathological examination of the left breast reveals a mixed ductal and papillary invasive carcinoma measuring 2.6 x 2 x 1.8 cm, with estrogen and progesterone receptors present in over 75% of neoplastic cell nuclei. The HER2 protein showed a score of 2+, but further verification by FISH indicated no HER2 gene amplification. Additionally, the axillary lymph nodes were negative for cancer, and there were findings of usual ductal hyperplasia and fibrocystic changes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) measuring 2.0 cm, with associated ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) comprising 60% of the tumor mass, both showing high nuclear grade and significant lymphovascular invasion. Surgical margins are negative for carcinoma, but the invasive component is close to the anterior margin, and one sentinel lymph node is negative for metastatic carcinoma. The invasive tumor cells are positive for estrogen and progesterone receptors and negative for HER-2.

The pathology report indicates that the biopsy of the distal esophagus reveals an invasive moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The tumor was composed of multiple fragments of soft tissue, and the entire specimen was submitted for analysis. Additionally, immunostaining for Her-2/neu showed that the tumor cells are immunonegative, scoring 0 out of 3.

The pathology report indicates that the tumor is located in the left occipito-temporal region. The histological diagnosis is glioblastoma multiforme. This diagnosis suggests a highly aggressive and malignant brain tumor.

The pathology report indicates that the excised tissues from the tongue, pharyngeal wall, and floor of mouth margins are negative for malignancy, confirming benign findings. However, carcinoma was identified in multiple lymph nodes, with one node entirely replaced by carcinoma and another showing extranodal extension, indicating advanced disease. The diagnosis includes moderate to poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma from the tonsillar pillar/floor of mouth, corresponding to AJCC Pathologic Stage IVA.

The pathology report indicates a clinical diagnosis of a brain tumor, specifically a diffuse astrocytoma. The microscopic examination reveals moderate nuclear polymorphism with a Ki-67 proliferation index of up to 7%. The final diagnosis is confirmed as diffuse astrocytoma, classified as Grade II.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a 1.6 cm invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the right upper lobe of the lung, with no evidence of angiolymphatic or visceral pleural invasion, and clear surgical resection margins. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization studies reveal low-level amplification of Her2/Neu, significant amplification of cyclin-D1, and high amplification of EGFR, which may correlate with poorer survival outcomes. All sampled lymph nodes are benign, and the pathologic stage is classified as T1 N0 Mx.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated perihilar cholangiocarcinoma (extrahepatic) arising from the right hepatic duct. A hepatic resection specimen measuring 20x20x11.5 cm revealed a prominent whitish nodule of 12x12x12 cm, along with multiple satellite lesions. The findings suggest invasion of lymphatic vessels and the gallbladder, classified as G2, pT3 according to UICC 2009 staging.

The pathology report indicates that a 41.2 g left adrenal specimen was obtained from a female patient during a laparoscopic left adrenalectomy, revealing two masses: a 2.2 cm pheochromocytoma and a 2.0 cm adrenal cortical adenoma, both of which were completely excised. The pheochromocytoma exhibited moderate cytoplasmic staining and a low proliferation index, with no evidence of vascular invasion or atypical mitoses. Additional molecular testing for SDHB germline mutation is recommended due to negative SDHB staining in the tumor.

The pathology report indicates that a mass excised from the right buttock was diagnosed as undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma, also referred to as malignant fibrous histiocytoma, with a size of 19 x 11 x 8 cm and a high histologic grade. The tumor exhibited a mitotic rate of 15 per 10 high-power fields and showed 30% necrosis, with the proximal margin being uninvolved while the distal margin was within 0.9 cm of the tumor. No additional pathologic findings or prior treatments were identified, and no lymph nodes were examined.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma (clear cell type) in the right lower pole tumor, measuring 4.7 cm, with a Fuhrman nuclear grade of 2 and tumor present at the margin of resection. The tumor is encapsulated and bulges into adjacent perinephric adipose tissue without gross infiltration, and there is no evidence of tumor in the perinephric fat or the 11th rib specimen. The report highlights that while the tumor is present at the inked margin, it does not invade the surrounding adipose tissue or indicate renal vein involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the patient, with a significant smoking history, has been diagnosed with invasive moderately-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the epiglottis, confirmed by recent biopsy. The specimen consisted of five mucosal fragments, which were examined microscopically, revealing both invasive carcinoma and carcinoma in situ. The findings suggest a serious condition requiring further clinical management.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrioid adenocarcinoma (FIGO grade 2) of the uterus, with a maximum depth of myometrial invasion of 0.8 cm and no lymphatic or vascular invasion noted. The cervix, serosa, and margins are free of tumor, and multiple lymph nodes from various sites are negative for carcinoma. Additional findings include a benign hernia sac and unremarkable right and left tubes and ovaries, with no significant pathologic alterations.

The pathology report indicates that the left axillary sentinel lymph node biopsy revealed two negative lymph nodes (0/2), suggesting no lymphatic spread of cancer. The left breast excisional biopsy confirmed the presence of invasive ductal carcinoma, grade 3, measuring 3.0 cm, with close proximity to the medial and inferior margins (less than 1 mm). No vessel invasion or ductal carcinoma in situ was identified, and the overall grade of the tumor is 9/9, indicating a high level of aggressiveness.

The pathology report indicates the presence of infiltrating squamous cell carcinoma primarily located at the base of the tongue, with a tumor size of 3.5 cm and extensive involvement of surrounding tissues, including the larynx. Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma was identified in multiple lymph nodes, with a total of 45 out of 91 lymph nodes affected, and evidence of extranodal extension. Additional biopsies from various sites, including the hypoglossal nerve and tonsils, were negative for tumor, while infiltrating squamous cells were noted in the left base of the tongue mucosa.

The pathology report indicates that a wedge resection of the right middle lobe revealed a 1.1 cm papillary predominant adenocarcinoma, with clear margins and no residual tumor detected. Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) testing for ALK gene rearrangement showed no evidence of rearrangement in the scored nuclei, although 26% of cells exhibited extra copies of the ALK gene, which is not uncommon in non-small cell lung cancer. Additionally, molecular studies for KRAS and EGFR mutations were negative, suggesting a potentially favorable prognosis regarding targeted therapies.

The pathology report indicates that the biopsy of a brain tumor in a 56-year-old woman reveals an astrocytoma classified as WHO grade 2, characterized by low histological grade features, positive IDH1-R132H, and a low MIB-1 proliferation index of 2%. There is no evidence of allelic loss on chromosome arms 1p and 19q, which is typically associated with oligodendrogliomas, suggesting that the tumor does not have the genetic profile commonly seen in that type. The microscopic examination shows diffuse infiltration of the cerebral cortex by the glioma, with no mitotic figures or tumor necrosis present.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade II, with a tumor size of 4.2 x 4.0 x 3.0 cm located in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast, along with focal ductal carcinoma in situ comprising approximately 5% of the tumor volume. All surgical margins are negative for tumor, and multiple left axillary sentinel lymph nodes are also negative for tumor involvement. Additional tests for estrogen and progesterone receptors and HER2/neu status have been ordered on the paraffin-embedded tissues.

The pathology report indicates the presence of moderately differentiated invasive squamous carcinoma affecting multiple structures, including the mandibular ramus, temporomandibular joint, palate, oropharynx, tongue, laryngeal cartilage, and bilateral neck soft tissue. The tumor measures 19.0 x 12.0 x 6.0 cm, and no tumor was found in the representative margins examined. The mandibular condyle is undergoing further processing after decalcification for additional evaluation.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has bilateral poorly differentiated prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4 + 3 = 7, involving both lobes of the prostate and measuring a maximum of 1.6 cm. The cancer is organ-confined with no evidence of extraprostatic extension, and all examined surgical margins and lymph nodes (26 total) are free of carcinoma. Additionally, multifocal high-grade prostatic intra-epithelial neoplasia is present, and perineural invasion is identified.

The pathology report indicates a poorly differentiated intestinal type adenocarcinoma located in the fundus of the stomach, measuring 9.5 x 8 x 1.2 cm and exhibiting ulceration. The tumor has metastasized to 6 out of 7 examined lymph nodes, with no specified lymphatic, venous, or perineural invasion, and the surgical margins are uninvolved. There is no evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment noted in the report.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of Grade 3 hepatocellular carcinoma in the right lobe of the liver, characterized by a dominant mass and a small satellite nodule, with clear surgical margins and no vascular invasion. The hepatic capsule is free of tumor, and the tumor exhibits a pushing type of infiltration. Additionally, the gallbladder shows mild chronic cholecystitis, while the non-neoplastic liver demonstrates mild tumor effect without evidence of chronic or primary liver disease.

The pathology report indicates the presence of multifocal papillary thyroid carcinoma in both lobes of the thyroid, with the largest tumor measuring 1.7 x 1.1 cm and evidence of focal extension into the surrounding soft tissue. Metastatic disease is confirmed in the left paratracheal lymph node (1/2) and both right paratracheal lymph nodes (2/2), as well as in one lymph node attached to the right thyroid. The pretracheal lymph node was negative for tumor, and the surgical margins from the total thyroidectomy were negative for tumor involvement.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade adenocarcinoma involving multiple sites, including the left adnexum, posterior cul-de-sac, uterus, and omentum, with a maximum tumor size of 27 cm. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is present in several lymph nodes, with a total of 3 positive nodes on the left and 1 on the right, while some biopsies from other areas are negative for tumor. The findings suggest advanced disease with a pathologic T stage of pT3a and N stage of pN1.

The pathology report indicates a poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma located in the left lung, measuring 62 mm, with invasion across the oblique fissure into the lower lobe and evidence of blood vessel invasion. The lymph nodes examined show no malignancy, but there is involvement of a peribronchial lymph node. The tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin, and the pathological stage is classified as T2N1MX.

The pathology report indicates a wedge resection of the liver revealing a solitary, trabecular pattern hepatocellular carcinoma measuring 2.4 x 2.2 cm, classified as Grade II. The tumor is confined to the liver with all margins negative except for the posterior margin, which is indeterminate due to encroachment. The background shows micronodular cirrhosis, and there is no evidence of lymph-vascular or perineural invasion, with a cancer stage of pT1, pNX.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of lung cancer, specifically squamous cell carcinoma. The tumor is classified as grade 2 and is staged as T2 N0 M1. No specific treatment details are provided, and the specimen was obtained from a blood draw.

The pathology report indicates a left kidney specimen with a central tumor measuring 9.5 cm, diagnosed as clear cell type renal cell carcinoma, Fuhrman grade 3. There is no evidence of malignancy in the renal capsule, renal sinus, or hilar margins, and vascular invasion is absent. The pTNM stage of the tumor is classified as T2a.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of metastatic high-grade serous papillary carcinoma involving multiple sites, including the omentum, abdominal wall, spleen, uterus, ovaries, and various lymph nodes. There is evidence of lymphovascular invasion and extensive tumor burden, with the carcinoma showing poorly differentiated features and significant involvement of serosal surfaces. The findings suggest a FIGO stage of IIIC, indicating advanced disease with widespread metastasis.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the apical segment of the right lower lobe, measuring 75 mm, with extensive endobronchial extension but no invasion of the visceral pleura. The bronchial resection margins are clear of tumor, although there is perineural permeation and involvement of a peribronchial lymph node. The pathological stage is classified as T2 N1, with additional findings of bronchiectasis and focal endogenous lipoid pneumonia in the adjacent lung parenchyma.

The pathology report indicates that a lobectomy of the right upper lobe revealed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal papillary features, measuring 4.3 cm, and the tumor invades the visceral pleura but has uninvolved margins. Biopsies of the right diaphragmatic nodule and multiple lymph nodes showed no evidence of malignancy, with the lymph nodes being negative for tumor and showing anthracosis. The overall findings suggest a localized lung adenocarcinoma with no regional lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of tubular adenocarcinoma of the rectum, characterized by a 3.3 x 3.4 x 0.7 cm ulcerous tumor that circumferentially surrounds the intestine and is classified as G2. Microscopic examination reveals infiltration into the mesorectal adipose tissue, with clear incision lines free of neoplastic lesions. Additionally, there are metastases identified in regional lymph nodes, classified as No III/VIII, indicating a more advanced stage of cancer (Dukes C, Astler-Coller C2, pT3, pNI, RO).

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic papillary serous carcinoma in multiple sites, including the omentum, both ovaries, and the uterus, with a high FIGO grade of 3 for the ovarian tumors. Additionally, there are multiple metastatic nodules identified in the bladder peritoneum, cecum, ileum, and rectosigmoid colon, as well as involvement of three external iliac lymph nodes. The cervix appears free of tumor, and a leiomyoma is noted in the myometrium of the uterus.

The pathology report indicates that the lymph nodes at levels 7 and 9 show anthracosis with reactive changes, but both are negative for malignancy. In contrast, the wedge resection of the right lower lobe lung reveals poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 1.6 cm, with extensive necrosis and extending to within 0.1 mm of the pleural surface, although no lymphovascular invasion is identified. The surgical margins are free of malignancy, and the frozen section diagnosis is confirmed.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a moderately differentiated colorectal adenocarcinoma located in the right hemicolectomy specimen, measuring 3 cm and exhibiting invasive spread through all layers of the intestinal wall. Additionally, a tubular adenoma with moderate epithelial dysplasia measuring 2.3 cm was found in the ascending colon, along with chronic appendicitis and periappendicitis related to the tumor's effect on the appendix. The tumor is staged as pT3, pNO, (0/40) LO vo; G2 RO, indicating significant local invasion and no lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates a unifocal clear cell renal carcinoma located in the lower pole of the right kidney, measuring 5.5 cm in greatest dimension, with a predominant histologic grade of II and a focal area of grade IV. The tumor is classified as pT1b, indicating it is more than 4 cm but not more than 7 cm in size and limited to the kidney, with uninvolved surgical margins and no evidence of invasion into the adrenal gland or large vessels. Additional findings include a renal cortical cyst and focal mild chronic interstitial inflammation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the right tongue, measuring 1.9 cm, with evidence of deep invasion into the lingual musculature and perineural invasion present. The resection margins are free of tumor, although the tumor is less than 1 mm from the deep margin. Additional evaluations of the dorsal and deep margins confirmed no tumor presence.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade II, with a tumor size of 1.5 x 1.2 x 1.0 cm, and ductal carcinoma in situ comprising 5-25% of the tumor volume. All surgical resection margins are negative for tumor, and multiple sentinel lymph nodes are also negative for metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, the report notes the presence of proliferative fibrocystic changes in the non-neoplastic breast parenchyma and identifies a fibroadenoma at the biopsy site.

The biopsy of the anterior urethral margin showed fibrofatty tissue with no tumor present. The prostatectomy revealed prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3+5=8, bilateral involvement, extraprostatic extension, and a positive tumor margin, while the seminal vesicles showed no carcinoma. Both left and right pelvic lymph node dissections were negative for carcinoma, with no cancer found in 18 lymph nodes examined.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of metastatic moderately differentiated squamous carcinoma involving a matted mass of subdigastric and upper posterior cervical lymph nodes, with evidence of extracapsular extension. No tumor was found in the examined margins of the nasopharynx, buccal mucosa, tongue, and other areas, indicating clear margins in those regions. Additionally, the report notes invasive moderately differentiated squamous carcinoma in the tongue, right retromolar trigone, hypopharynx, uvula, and soft palate, with a maximum depth of invasion of 1.4 cm and focal perineural invasion present.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 1.7 cm, with no invasion of the pleura and negative margins for tumor in bronchial and vascular areas. Additionally, two hilar lymph nodes were excised and found to be negative for tumor, and two pleural plaques were noted in the non-neoplastic lung. The pathologic stage is classified as T1NoMx, indicating early-stage lung cancer.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) located in the liver, measuring 2.8 x 2.5 x 2.3 cm, with 20% tumor necrosis and no satellite nodules. The surgical margins are free of tumor, and there is evidence of chronic hepatitis due to HBV, along with moderate steatosis and septal fibrosis (stage 3). Additionally, the gallbladder shows chronic inflammation and cholelithiasis.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a cholecystectomy revealing a fundal adenomyoma and one benign lymph node, with no dysplasia or malignancy detected. The appendectomy showed no diagnostic alterations, while the total gastrectomy revealed a moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma (2.9 cm) at the gastric cardia, with lymphovascular invasion and two out of twenty-five lymph nodes positive for metastasis, resulting in a pathologic stage of IIB. The margins from the surgical resection were negative for malignancy, and no perineural invasion was identified.

The pathology report indicates that multiple lymph nodes from the left neck dissection (levels 2A, 2B, 3, and 4) and various margins were negative for tumor involvement. However, a composite resection of the left mandible, buccal, and floor of mouth revealed well-differentiated invasive squamous carcinoma measuring 5.0 cm, with invasion into the bone and a depth of 0.7 cm. The anterior mandible margin was reported as negative for tumor, while perineural and vascular invasion assessments are pending.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, extending into the adjacent chest wall, with negative margins and no evidence of metastatic carcinoma in the sampled hilar lymph nodes. Additionally, non-necrotizing granulomatous lymphadenitis was observed in multiple lymph nodes, but special stains for acid-fast and fungal organisms were negative. Overall, the findings suggest a locally advanced lung cancer with no distant metastasis and benign changes in the lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of multifocal papillary carcinoma, follicular variant, in the right lobe of the thyroid, with the largest tumor measuring 1.0 cm and an additional 0.3 cm focus. Both examined lymph nodes are negative for tumor, and there is no evidence of vascular or lymphatic invasion, with uninvolved margins. Additional findings include nodular hyperplasia and chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis consistent with Hashimoto's thyroiditis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated serous adenocarcinoma (FIGO Grade III) in the left ovary, with no residual ovarian tissue identified. Metastatic serous adenocarcinoma is present on the ovarian surface and in the right upper quadrant peritoneum, small intestine mesentery, and omentum, with a maximum dimension of tumor implants outside the true pelvis measuring 5 cm. The final staging is classified as at least FIGO Stage IIIC, with regional lymph node status and distant tumor sites not assessable.

The pathology report indicates that the right tonsil excisional biopsies reveal moderately differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma, with cancer extending to the tissue edges. HPV testing has been requested and will be reported separately. The gross description details multiple fragments of tissue from the right tonsil, with a frozen section diagnosis of at least squamous cell carcinoma in situ.

The pathology report indicates that the left kidney mass is diagnosed as papillary renal cell carcinoma, type 2, measuring 7.5 cm, with no definitive extrarenal extension and clear vascular and ureteral margins. The para-aortic lymph nodes were excised, and no tumor was found in any of the 33 lymph nodes examined. Cytogenetic analysis revealed an abnormal mosaic karyotype, with findings including missing the Y chromosome and an extra copy of chromosome 7 in some cells.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a choroidal melanoma in the enucleated left eye, measuring 16mm in diameter and 12mm in height, with a mixed cell type consisting predominantly of spindle cells. Histological examination reveals a dome-shaped tumor with a significant exudative retinal detachment, high mitotic activity, and no evidence of scleral invasion or extraocular growth. Molecular genetic analysis shows monosomy 3 and gains in chromosome 8, which will be correlated with clinical data for assessing metastatic risk.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has poorly differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma, which measures 11.6 cm and shows lymphovascular invasion and extensive necrosis, with tumor extension through the liver capsule. Biopsies from Gerota's fascia and omentum show no evidence of malignancy, while additional biopsies from Gerota's fascia confirm the presence of poorly differentiated carcinoma. The findings are consistent with the patient's clinical history of a liver mass previously diagnosed as poorly differentiated carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the esophagus, with extensive necrosis and invasion into the muscularis propria, measuring 4.2 cm at the gastroesophageal junction. One out of thirteen examined lymph nodes showed metastatic carcinoma, while the resection margins were negative for neoplasm. No intestinal metaplasia or vascular invasion was noted, and the presence of multiple possible lymph nodes was documented, with the largest measuring 1.2 cm.

The pathology report indicates that the right ovary and fallopian tube, as well as left adnexal tissue and omentum, are negative for malignancy. The uterus shows a high-grade serous carcinoma measuring 4.8 x 4.0 x 3.0 cm with myometrial invasion of 1.5 cm, but no cervical involvement or lymphovascular invasion is identified. All examined lymph nodes from various regions are negative for metastatic disease, and the surgical margins are uninvolved.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a tumor with oligodendroglial and astrocytic differentiation, featuring minigemistocytes. The proliferation index is noted to be 8%. The final diagnosis is an Anaplastic Oligoastrocytoma classified as WHO grade III.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade poorly differentiated endometrial carcinoma, with histologic features suggestive of serous carcinoma, and evidence of lymphovascular invasion, but no cervical stromal involvement or metastasis to lymph nodes. The tumor invades less than half the thickness of the myometrium, measuring 3.0 x 2.7 x 1.5 cm, and shows negative immunoreactivity for p53, estrogen receptor (ER), and progesterone receptor (PR). Additional findings include adenomyosis, and all examined lymph nodes and omentum were negative for tumor, with the overall staging classified as pT1a N0 M0 according to AJCC and FIGO criteria.

The pathology report indicates that the excised lymph node from the hepatic artery is negative for metastatic carcinoma. A pancreatic endocrine neoplasm, grade 2, was identified in the subtotal pancreatectomy and splenectomy specimen, measuring 3 x 2.5 cm, with free surgical margins and no regional lymph node metastasis. Additionally, the gallbladder showed chronic cholecystitis and cholesterolosis without evidence of dysplasia or malignancy.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, conventional type, with 90% clear cells and 10% eosinophilic cells, classified as Fuhrman's nuclear grade 4, measuring 4.5 cm in maximum dimension. The tumor is confined to the kidney without extension into the perinephric adipose tissue, and both vascular and ureteral margins are free of tumor, with one lymph node showing no evidence of malignancy. The tumor exhibits focal bulging into the renal sinus adipose tissue but lacks infiltrative borders, and there are areas of marked anaplasia that are not indicative of sarcomatoid dedifferentiation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme, WHO grade IV, with a high proportion of necrosis ranging from 30% to 50% across multiple biopsy samples. Immunohistochemical analysis shows weak MGMT staining (15%), loss of PTEN, and absence of pMAPK, suggesting potential responsiveness to Temodar and radiation therapy. Additionally, the expression levels of laminin beta-1 and beta-2 indicate a more favorable prognosis, despite the aggressive nature of the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast, with a tumor size of 3.5 cm located in the inner upper quadrant. Metastases were identified in the axillary lymph nodes, classified as NHG3, pT2, pN1a. Immunohistochemical analysis revealed no estrogen or progesterone receptors, and HER2 testing showed a negative reaction in the invasive carcinoma cells.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a right neck dissection and total thyroidectomy, revealing metastatic papillary carcinoma in multiple lymph nodes across levels II, III, and IV, as well as in the right paratracheal neck dissection. The total thyroid examination showed a 2.2 cm papillary thyroid carcinoma with extension into adjacent parathyroid tissue and tumor present at the margin. Additionally, one lymph node in level II exhibited a psammoma body surrounded by giant cells, but no epithelial cells were identified, and a cytokeratin stain was negative for metastatic carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 27 mm, with pleural invasion but clear margins from the bronchial resection. Metastatic carcinoma is identified in the hilar lymph nodes, while the No. 10 lymph node shows no evidence of malignancy. Additionally, the non-neoplastic lung exhibits emphysema and fibrosis with a usual interstitial pneumonia-like pattern.

The pathology report indicates that all examined pelvic lymph nodes from both the right and left sides are benign, with no evidence of malignancy. A radical prostatectomy revealed prostatic adenocarcinoma, acinar type, with a Gleason score of 3 + 5 - 8, involving both lobes of the prostate and showing focal perineural invasion, but no extraprostatic extension or lymphatic invasion. The tumor comprises approximately 10% of the prostate volume, with a maximum diameter of 1.3 cm, and all surgical margins are free of tumor.

The pathology report indicates that a thymectomy was performed, revealing a cortical thymoma classified as B2 by the WHO, which is encapsulated and completely excised with free surgical margins. There is no evidence of lymphatic or vascular invasion, and the pericardium is present but not involved by the tumor. The tumor is characterized as pT1, Nx, Mx, and the surrounding thymus tissue does not show signs of lymphoid hyperplasia.

The pathology report indicates a 6.5 cm keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus, classified as well differentiated (G-1), with superficial ulceration and invasion into the muscularis propria. Metastasis was found in two out of ten examined lymph nodes, specifically one paraesophageal and one along the a. gastrica sinistra. There is no evidence of venous invasion, and the surgical margins are uninvolved, indicating complete resection of the primary tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated endometrial carcinoma, with the tumor extensively involving the endometrial cavity and invading the myometrium and cervix. The tumor measures 3.4 x 3.0 x 2.0 cm and is classified as FIGO grade 3, with lymphovascular space invasion present but surgical margins and regional lymph nodes free of metastatic carcinoma. Additional findings include benign fibroadipose tissue in the omentum and endosalpingiosis in the ovaries, with a recommendation for clinical correlation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma with extensive spindle cell differentiation, also referred to as gliosarcoma, affecting the left temporal lobe of the brain, as well as the leptomeninges, dura mater, and skull. Intraoperative consultations suggested the presence of meningioma, at least Grade 2, in the examined specimens. The report includes details on the gross description of the tumor and associated tissues, with multiple fragments submitted for analysis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma in a liver mass measuring 5.5 x 5.0 x 7.0 cm, with the tumor confined to the hepatic parenchyma and no invasion of surgical margins or surrounding structures. Additionally, the gallbladder shows signs of chronic cholecystitis, and no tumor was found in the pericystic lymph node biopsy. The remaining liver parenchyma is noted to have cirrhosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrial adenocarcinoma, endometrioid type, FIGO grade 3, with superficial myometrial invasion. The cervix, ovaries, and left fallopian tube are free of malignancy, while the right fallopian tube was not identified. Additionally, excised pelvic lymph nodes from both sides show no evidence of malignancy, with an incidental finding of remote fat necrosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma, follicular variant, located in the left thyroid lobe, measuring 2.2 cm, with no multifocality or extrathyroidal extension. Lymphovascular invasion is present, but the resection margins are negative, and no lymph nodes were identified in the specimen. The gross examination reveals a well-circumscribed nodule confined to the thyroid, with an unremarkable isthmus.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder specimen shows chronic cholecystitis, while the liver specimen reveals chronic hepatitis consistent with hepatitis B (grade 2, stage 2) and poorly differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma, with the resection margins being uninvolved. The liver lesion is described as irregularly circumscribed and lobulated, with some areas abutting the serosal surface and close to the surgical margin. Additionally, there is evidence of iron overload in the liver tissue.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a modified radical mastectomy for left breast cancer, revealing a poorly differentiated infiltrating duct carcinoma measuring 4.0 cm, with one intramammary lymph node showing metastatic carcinoma. No metastatic disease was found in the 37 examined axillary lymph nodes, and the closest margin was 1 mm from the invasive tumor. The tumor is classified as nuclear grade III with a Nottingham score of 9, and the overall staging is determined to be 2B.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder specimen shows no pathological diagnosis, while the liver specimen reveals well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma of the solid variant, which is involving the deep margin, alongside chronic hepatitis C with mild activity and cirrhosis.
