The pathology report indicates an extended right hemicolectomy specimen with a diagnosis of invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma located at the hepatic flexure, measuring 4.8 x 3.2 cm and extending through the full thickness of the colonic wall to the serosal surface. The tumor is classified as pT4a, with negative proximal and distal margins, but it is noted to be within 1 mm of the circumferential margin, and there are areas suspicious for vascular invasion. Additionally, no regional lymph node involvement was found (0/25 lymph nodes), and other findings include an ileocecal valve lipoma and fibrous obliteration of the appendix tip.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of well-differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lung, with multiple tumor deposits in both the upper and lower lobes, the largest measuring 165 mm in diameter. The visceral pleura is focally involved, but there is no surface involvement, and the bronchial resection margin is clear, although the peri-hilar margin is closely approached. Additionally, one hilar lymph node shows direct extension of the tumor, while the remaining lymph nodes are free of malignancy, and the pathological stage is classified as T4 N1 M1.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a left frontal brain tumor diagnosed as glioblastoma (WHO grade IV) following an excision biopsy. The MGMT promoter methylation analysis was performed and found to be positive, indicating the presence of a methylated MGMT promoter. Microscopic examination revealed a high-grade astrocytic neoplasm with pleomorphic features, frequent mitotic figures, and extensive microvascular proliferation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade malignant fibrous histiocytoma (MFH) in the right anterior thigh, with a tumor size of 12.3 x 8.2 x 6.6 cm that involves skeletal muscle. The tumor exhibits areas of necrosis and significant mitotic activity, extending to within 1 mm of an inked margin. The specimen was received fresh and gross examination revealed a well-circumscribed soft tumor surrounded by a thin membrane.

The pathology report indicates that a right partial nephrectomy was performed, revealing a unifocal papillary renal cell carcinoma, type 2, with a greatest dimension of 4.8 cm and a Fuhrman grade of 3 out of 4. The tumor is confined to the kidney, with no evidence of cancer at the resection margin or involvement of surrounding structures. Pathologic staging is classified as pT1b, with no significant findings in the nonneoplastic kidney or hilar lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive high-grade urothelial carcinoma in the bladder and prostate, with associated carcinoma in situ and a positive margin at the right distal ureter. All examined pelvic lymph nodes (18 total) were negative for neoplasm, suggesting no regional lymph node metastasis. The tumor measures 5 cm and invades the muscularis propria, with the prostatic urethra also showing involvement by carcinoma in situ, while the prostate itself exhibits benign prostatic hyperplasia.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated cervical adenosquamous carcinoma, which invades the cervical wall and is located less than 0.1 mm from the resection margins. All examined lymph nodes from the left pelvic, right pelvic, and para-aortic regions were negative for carcinoma, with no evidence of metastasis. Additional findings include endometrial polyps and endometriosis in the ovaries and fallopian tubes.

The pathology report indicates an invasive, mucinous adenocarcinoma of the colon classified as G3, with tumor penetration through all parietal layers (pT3) and evidence of vascular infiltrates (L1, V1). The resection margins are free of tumor, with normal mucosa, submucosa, and muscularis, and no lymph node involvement (pNO, 0 of 13). Additionally, there are tubulovillous adenomas with focally severe dysplasia and reactive lesions in the omental tissue.

The pathology report indicates that the left breast lumpectomy revealed an infiltrating ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade 2, with a tumor size of 1.3 cm and no evidence of necrosis, vascular invasion, or microcalcifications. All examined sentinel and non-sentinel lymph nodes were negative for malignancy, confirming no lymphatic spread of the cancer. The tumor was estrogen and progesterone receptor positive, with a HER2/neu status of negative, and the pathological stage is classified as pT1c N0 (i-) MX.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma, follicular variant, measuring 6.0 cm, confined to the left thyroid lobe with grossly free margins. No parathyroid tissue was identified in the left inferior parathyroid and right parathyroid specimens, while the right thyroid lobe showed no tumor presence. Additionally, the left paratracheal dissection revealed fibroadipose tissue without any lesions or lymph nodes identified.

The pathology report indicates that the right renal mass is diagnosed as renal cell carcinoma of the conventional (clear cell) type, with a Fuhrman Nuclear Grade of III/IV and a tumor size of 4.0 cm, but without local or renal vein invasion, and with free surgical margins. Additional specimens from the right peritumoral fat and the right lower pole of the kidney show benign fibroadipose tissue and benign renal cortical parenchyma with focal glomerulosclerosis, respectively. The report also notes that the proximal right ureter specimen reveals benign partially denuded urothelium and urethral wall.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of well-differentiated classical papillary thyroid carcinoma with tall cell features, located in the right lobe of the thyroid, measuring 1.1 cm, with focal capsular invasion but no blood vessel invasion or extrathyroid extension. The surgical margins are free of tumor, and the non-neoplastic thyroid shows nodular hyperplasia. Additionally, a left paratracheal cyst was excised, which is benign and lined by cuboidal epithelium, with four benign lymph nodes also identified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of chromophobe renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, with a tumor size of 9.5 cm and surgical margins free of tumor (R0). The tumor is classified as Grade 2 and staged as pT2a, with no evidence of lymphovascular invasion or regional lymph node involvement (pNX). The overall pathologic stage is II, and the findings in the non-neoplastic kidney are unremarkable.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma measuring 2.1 cm, with negative surgical margins and no evidence of vascular invasion or capsule invasion. The liver is noted to be cirrhotic, specifically cryptogenic cirrhosis. Additionally, the gallbladder resection showed no significant abnormalities.

The pathology report describes a 10 cm soft gray to reddish tumor located in the right adrenal gland, with a lighter-colored area measuring approximately 4 cm. Histological examination reveals a composition of zellballen, marked pleomorphic nuclei, and focal melanin pigmentation, along with areas showing ganglionic differentiation. The final diagnosis is pheochromocytoma, with no evidence of vascular invasion.

The pathology report indicates the presence of keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in the larynx, with a tumor size of 5.5 cm and histological grade 2, involving various structures including the right vocal cord and cartilage. Metastatic carcinoma is identified in several lymph nodes, with three out of sixteen lymph nodes on the right side and one out of ten on the right recurrent lymph node showing capsular involvement. The left side lymph nodes are largely uninvolved, and there is no evidence of vascular or perineural invasion, with surgical margins and tracheal margin also uninvolved by neoplasia.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the ascending colon, classified as G2 and pT3. The tumor was resected with tumor-free margins, and there is infiltration into the perimuscular fatty tissue. Importantly, there are no local lymph node metastases, with a total of 34 lymph nodes examined showing no evidence of cancer spread (pN0).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of Diffuse Large B-cell Lymphoma (DLBCL) based on the immunoprofile, which shows positivity for CD20 and CD79a, while being negative for CD3, CD5, CD10, and Cyclin D1. The tumor exhibits a diffuse pattern with medium to large-sized cells and a high proliferation index (Ki 67/MIB1) of 80-90%. The biopsy was taken from a left supraclavicular lymph node, and the findings are consistent with malignant lymphoma.

The histopathological examination of the left breast reveals an invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 3.9 x 6.6 x 2.8 cm, with metastases found in 11 out of 13 axillary lymph nodes. Immunohistochemical analysis shows estrogen receptors in 75% and progesterone receptors in 10% of neoplastic cell nuclei, while HER2 testing indicates a score of 2+ with no gene amplification detected by FISH. The tumor is classified as NHG2, pT3, pN3a, indicating a moderate grade and advanced stage of cancer.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the stomach, characterized by a 9 cm circular tumor located in the antral part, with invasion into all wall layers and the omentum. Out of fifteen examined lymph nodes, eleven showed evidence of metastasis, and the surgical margins are involved with tumor. There is no evidence of venous invasion, but the tumor exhibits a diffusely infiltrating pattern, consistent with linitis plastica.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of small-cell urothelial carcinoma, comprising 90% of the tumor, measuring 4.5 cm, with infiltration into perivesical fatty tissue and lymph vessels, along with a lymph node metastasis of 0.9 cm. The surgical resection margins are tumor-free, and there are multifocal areas of carcinoma in situ in the remaining urothelium. Immunohistochemical analysis supports the diagnosis, showing diffuse positivity for pan-cytokeratin AE1/AE3 and high positivity for synaptophysin and NSE, confirming the poorly differentiated nature of the carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma, conventional type, in the left thyroid lobe, measuring 2.5 cm, with extrathyroidal extension and lymphovascular invasion, but negative resection margins. The right thyroid lobe shows multinodular adenomatous goiter with no evidence of tumor. The background thyroid condition is characterized by a multinodular adenomatous goiter.

The pathology report indicates a malignant tumor identified as Serous Papillary Cystadenocarcinoma located in the ovary, measuring 3.5x2.2x1.8 cm. Microscopic examination reveals solid nests and papillary patterns of large cells with moderately pleomorphic, hyperchromatic nuclei, along with areas of cystic degeneration and focal necrosis. Additionally, part of the deep resection margin is involved, suggesting incomplete removal of the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma in the left breast, with a histologic grade of 2 out of 3 and a gross tumor size of 1.6 cm. The surgical margins are negative, and there is less than 10% in-situ carcinoma present, characterized as solid and cribriform. Estrogen receptor activity is positive, while progesterone receptor activity is negative, with further analysis pending.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive lobular adenocarcinoma of the left breast, identified through a stereotactic needle core biopsy of a spiculated mass with pleomorphic calcifications. The Nottingham combined histologic grade is 2 out of 3, with associated in-situ lobular carcinoma and microcalcifications present. Estrogen/progesterone receptor, HER2/Neu, and EGFR analyses are pending for further evaluation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of right renal cell carcinoma, clear cell type, with focal spindle cell features and a nuclear grade of III/IV, measuring 8.0 cm in greatest diameter, and extending through the renal capsule but confined within Gerota's fascia. The report also notes the presence of a small angiomylipoma and confirms that all surgical margins are free of tumor, with no invasion of the renal vein identified. Additionally, nine paracaval lymph nodes were examined, all of which were benign.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 6 cm with central cavitation and arterial invasion. The bronchial margin is suspicious for tumor, and one of the five examined peribronchial lymph nodes shows carcinoma by direct extension. Other lymph nodes and excised tissues from various levels are negative for metastatic disease, and there are findings of obstructive pneumonia and acute bronchopneumonia.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in both breasts, with Nottingham grades of 3 and 2, respectively, and a maximum tumor size of 2.0 cm in the left breast. Sentinel lymph node biopsies from both axillae are negative for metastatic tumor involvement. The invasive tumor cells are positive for estrogen and progesterone receptors and negative for HER-2, with lymphovascular space invasion identified but negative surgical margins.

The pathology report indicates that the excised lymph node at level 9R was negative for metastatic tumor, while the right upper lobe lobectomy revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.7 cm, with negative margins and no visceral pleura invasion. Additional lymph nodes excised from levels 7, 10R, and 4R were all negative for metastatic tumor, although some contained calcified granulomas and rare yeast forms consistent with Histoplasma capsulatum. The true proximal bronchial margin was also negative for malignancy, confirming the absence of invasive carcinoma at the margins.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive ductal adenocarcinoma in the head of the pancreas, with chronic pancreatitis noted in the body of the pancreas. Additionally, metastatic adenocarcinoma is found in the hepatic artery lymph node and multiple periduodenal lymph nodes, with low-grade dysplasia observed at the bile duct margin. The tumor measures 6.1 x 4.5 x 2.0 cm and extends to the lateral resection margins, involving the duodenal mucosa and demonstrating lymphovascular and perineural invasion.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the left vocal fold, with a tumor size of 5.0 x 3.0 cm affecting multiple laryngeal structures and adjacent soft tissues. Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma was found in one of the left neck lymph nodes, while all right neck lymph nodes showed no evidence of neoplasia. Additionally, the left soft tissue margins were involved by neoplasia, while other surgical margins remained uninvolved.

The pathology report describes a hypercellular glial neoplasm with both astrocytic and oligodendrocytic components, showing moderate cytologic atypia and diffuse infiltration into adjacent brain tissue. The presence of microvascular proliferation and early micronecrosis raises concerns for anaplastic progression, despite low mitotic activity suggesting a low-grade glioma. The final diagnosis is an oligoastrocytoma with early anaplastic progression, supported by a MIB-1 labeling index of 6.9%.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated serous adenocarcinoma in multiple sites, including the left gutter, omental tumor with small bowel, left pelvic sidewall, cul de sac, and perirectal tissue. The right ovary shows serous adenocarcinoma, while the left ovary and fallopian tube are unremarkable, and lymph nodes from the omentum are negative for malignancy. The overall pathologic stage is classified as pT3c pNX pMX, indicating advanced disease with metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that a right hemimandibulectomy was performed, revealing an invasive well-differentiated squamous carcinoma with margins free of tumor. The specimen measured 15.0 x 2.5 x 1.5 cm, and a soft tissue fragment with an ulcerated and necrotic lesion was noted within it. Decalcification of the mandibular bone confirmed involvement of the cortical bone by the carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive poorly differentiated endometrioid adenocarcinoma with squamous differentiation (FIGO Grade 3) in the endometrium, which invades the myometrium to a depth of 10 mm. There is no evidence of lymphovascular invasion or regional lymph node metastasis, as all examined lymph nodes (24 total) are free of malignancy. Additional findings include a leiomyoma and focal granulomatous inflammation in the ovaries, but no malignancy is detected in the cervix or fallopian tubes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the sigmoid colon, measuring 4.4 cm in length and 3.7 cm in width, with invasion into the muscularis propria but no evidence of vascular or perineural invasion. Surgical margins are free of tumor, and no regional lymph node metastases were identified among the 17 examined nodes. Additionally, multiple hyperplastic polyps were noted away from the carcinoma, and a preexisting tubulovillous polyp was found at the carcinoma site.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of clear cell renal carcinoma (Fuhrman grade 3) in a right kidney specimen, measuring 6.3 x 5 x 4 cm, with the tumor confined to the kidney and not extending through the capsule. The tumor is classified as pT1b, indicating it is between 4-7 cm in size and limited to the kidney, with no evidence of lymphatic or venous invasion. Margins are uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, and regional lymph nodes and distant metastasis could not be assessed.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of prostate adenocarcinoma following a radical prostatectomy, with the tumor involving approximately half of the prostate and classified with a Gleason score of 7 (3+4). There is no evidence of extraprostatic extension, seminal vesicle involvement, or lymphovascular invasion, and the surgical margins are negative for tumor involvement. The pTNM stage is reported as pT2c, and high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia (PIN) is noted.

The pathology report indicates that a total organ resection of the stomach was performed on a female patient, revealing a 5.3 x 3.9 x 1.8 cm tubular adenocarcinoma (G2, intestinal type) located on the front wall of the stomach. Microscopic examination confirmed the presence of metastases in lymph nodes associated with both the lesser and greater curvature of the stomach. The final histopathological diagnosis is tubular adenocarcinoma of the stomach with lymph node metastases (G2, pT2, pN2).

The pathology report indicates that the left breast excision revealed an invasive ductal carcinoma measuring 1.6 cm, with the tumor located 0.2 cm from the inferior surgical margin and classified as SBR Grade 3. The sentinel lymph node analysis showed no evidence of metastasis, with a negative result for tumor involvement. Additional margins examined showed no tumor presence, confirming clear margins in the excised breast tissue.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade invasive urothelial carcinoma of the bladder, with evidence of lymphovascular invasion. The specimen consists of multiple fragments of bladder wall tissue showing chronic inflammation and granulation tissue, consistent with a previous biopsy site. The tumor measures 2.2 x 1.1 x 0.5 cm and has been submitted entirely for examination.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a radical prostatectomy revealing invasive poorly differentiated prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4+4 (total score of 8), affecting both lobes of the prostate and showing multifocal extraprostatic extension. All examined lymph nodes from the right and left pelvic regions (34 total) showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma, and all surgical margins were free of tumor. Additionally, perineural invasion was identified, and multifocal high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia was present.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has been diagnosed with papillary renal cell carcinoma type 2, measuring 8.5 cm, which involves the renal sinus and perinephric fat, with evidence of extracapsular extension. Four out of five hilar lymph nodes show metastatic involvement, while no tumor was found in the examined paracaval lymph nodes or the peri renal fat. Surgical resection margins are clear of carcinoma, and the remaining lymph nodes and fat around the kidney are benign.

The pathology report indicates the presence of two nodules in the right adrenal gland, measuring 6.2 cm and 3.1 cm, consistent with a pheochromocytoma. Both tumors are encapsulated, with the larger tumor exhibiting signs of fresh bleeding and focal necrosis, while the smaller tumor shows no necrosis. Immunohistochemical analysis confirms the diagnosis of pheochromocytoma, and the surgical margins appear to be free of tumor, with no evidence of ectopic ACTH production.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade carcinosarcoma in the endometrium, with the tumor forming a necrotic mass that fills the endometrial cavity and invades the lower uterine segment and cervical canal. The tumor has penetrated 2.5 cm into the myometrium and shows evidence of angiolymphatic invasion, along with focal superficial invasion of the cervical stroma. Additionally, a calcified subserosal leiomyoma is noted, and preliminary frozen section consultation suggested a high-grade carcinoma, likely serous, pending further classification on permanent sections.

The pathology report indicates that the surgical margins are clear (R0), suggesting complete removal of the tumor. It also identifies a villous adenoma with areas of severe dysplasia, classified as high-risk intraepithelial neoplasia, along with a serrated adenoma. Additionally, the lymph nodes examined are free of disease (pN0).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma of the cecum, arising from a tubulovillous adenoma, with full muscle wall thickness invasion and metastasis to 2 out of 10 examined pericolic lymph nodes. The tumor measures 4 x 3.7 x 3.5 cm, and the proximal and distal margins of resection are negative for tumor. Additionally, the liver biopsy shows metastatic adenocarcinoma consistent with the cecal adenocarcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a WHO Grade 3 oligoastrocytoma, predominantly oligodendroglial, located in the left frontal region of the brain. The tumor measures 4.0 x 3.2 x 1.8 cm and exhibits notable nodularity and satellitosis. Additionally, 1p19q deletion was confirmed through FISH studies performed on a previous specimen.

The pathology report indicates a right upper lobectomy performed for poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the lung, measuring 75 mm, with vascular invasion and metastatic carcinoma identified in a peribronchial lymph node. There is no evidence of pleural invasion, and the bronchial resection margin is clear of malignancy but contains a benign mucous gland adenoma. Additionally, a separate pleural nodule is identified as a silicotic nodule, and the pathological stage is classified as T2 N1.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4+3=7, showing bilateral involvement and multifocal extraprosthetic extension, with approximately 25% of the examined prostate sections affected. The surgical margins are negative, but there is bilateral involvement of the seminal vesicles and vasa deferentia, while lymphatic and venous invasion are absent. Both right and left pelvic lymph nodes are reported as benign, confirming no metastatic disease in these lymphatic structures.

The pathology report describes a moderately hypercellular glial neoplasm characterized by atypical fibrillary astrocytes and the presence of bizarre, multinucleated cells, but without microvascular proliferation or tumor necrosis. The cytologic features indicate anaplastic characteristics, with a calculated MIB-1 labeling index of 6.5%, suggesting moderate proliferation. The final diagnosis is anaplastic astrocytoma Grade III.

The pathology report describes a brain tissue sample weighing 2.0g, which shows signs of a neuroepithelial neoplasm with marked infiltration into the neocortex. Microscopic examination reveals characteristics consistent with a WHO grade II oligodendroglioma, including round nuclei, scant cytoplasm, and neuronal satellitosis. The tumor exhibits areas of increased cellularity and microcysts, but no microvascular proliferation was observed.

The pathology report indicates that the left adrenal gland resection revealed a low-grade adenocortical carcinoma characterized by low mitotic activity, capsular, and vascular invasion. The Ki-67 proliferation marker shows a proliferation rate above that typically found in benign tumors, and additional immunohistochemical studies support the diagnosis. The tumor measures 6.2 x 5.3 x 6.0 cm with focal areas of necrosis and abuts the surgical margin, while a small segment of normal adrenal gland is also present.

The pathology report indicates that both specimens from the brain tumor are diagnosed as glioblastoma, classified as WHO grade IV. The tumor was identified in the frontal region and consisted of multiple irregularly-shaped soft tissue fragments. A craniotomy was performed for the evaluation of the brain mass.

The pathology report indicates that the total gastrectomy specimen shows extensive infiltration by poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, characterized by a linitis plastica pattern, with full thickness wall infiltration and metastases in all examined lymph nodes. The tumor extends to the gastro-oesophageal junction but does not involve the surgical margins. Additionally, a right gastroepiploic lymph node also demonstrates metastatic adenocarcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive colonic adenocarcinoma located in the right colon, measuring 3.4 cm in diameter, with a low histologic grade (grade 2 of 4) and no lymphovascular or perineural invasion identified. The tumor has invaded to the junction between the muscularis propria and subserosal soft tissues, with clear margins and no metastases found in the examined regional lymph nodes. Additional findings include a submucosal lipoma and fibrous obliteration of the distal appendiceal lumen, with normal expression of mismatch repair proteins, and the case is staged as pT2 pNO.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a malignant mixed Mullerian tumor (MMMT) with heterologous differentiation, extensively involving the lower uterine segment and invading the myometrium to a depth of 13 mm. Metastatic involvement of the tumor is identified in two out of six right pelvic lymph nodes, with extracasular extension, while the left pelvic lymph nodes show no evidence of malignancy. The overall pathologic AJCC stage of the tumor is classified as Stage IIIC, indicating significant local and regional spread.

The pathology report indicates an excised skin lesion from the hip, measuring 2 x 2.5 cm, which is diagnosed as malignant melanoma with ulcerated and pigmented features. Breslow's depth is noted to be 5 mm, and the margins are uninvolved, suggesting complete excision. There is no evidence of venous invasion, while details regarding lymph nodes and other features are not specified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, specifically the conventional (clear cell) type, with a Fuhrman Nuclear Grade of II/IV and a tumor size of 3.5 cm. The tumor is classified as pT1, indicating it is limited to the kidney without local invasion or renal vein involvement, and the surgical margins are free of tumor. The non-neoplastic kidney tissue is unremarkable, and no adrenal gland or lymph nodes were identified in the submitted specimens.

The pathology report indicates that the excised right and left pelvic lymph nodes show no evidence of malignancy, with all 57 examined lymph nodes being benign. However, the radical prostatectomy specimen reveals extensive prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4+5=9, indicating a high-grade tumor that extensively involves both lobes of the prostate and shows extraprostatic extension and perineural invasion. Additionally, there is focal involvement of the surgical margin, and the tumor comprises approximately 50-60% of the sampled prostate gland volume.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma measuring 2.5 cm, with invasion depth of 0.7 cm, but no lymphovascular space invasion identified. Resection margins are free of carcinoma, and no carcinoma was found in the examined lymph nodes or other structures, including the vagina, uterus, and ovaries. Additional findings include para-ovarian and peritubal adhesions, as well as hydrosalpinx, but no dysplasia or carcinoma was noted in the radical hysterectomy specimens.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of conventional clear cell renal carcinoma in the right kidney, with a tumor size of 8.1 cm and Fuhrman Nuclear Grade III/IV, showing local invasion into renal sinus fat and involvement of the renal vein. The excised lymph nodes were benign, with no evidence of metastasis, and the right adrenal gland was also found to be benign. The overall staging for the renal cell carcinoma is pT3a, indicating invasion into surrounding tissues but not beyond Gerota's fascia.

The pathology report indicates that multiple lymph nodes (4R, 4L, level 7, 2R, and additional 4R) were biopsied, and all were negative for carcinoma. A lobectomy of the right upper lobe revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.0 cm, with focal invasion into the visceral pleura, but the bronchial margin was negative for tumor. Additionally, no malignancy was identified in nine lymph nodes examined, and there were findings of hyalinized plaques in the parietal pleura.

The pathology report indicates a clinical diagnosis of a brain tumor. The gross examination revealed dense-elastic pieces of grayish-brownish brain tissue from the left temporal lobe. Microscopic analysis confirmed the presence of anaplastic astrocytoma, Grade III.

The pathology report indicates a colectomy specimen from the sigmoid colon, revealing a 5.2 x 2.2 cm infiltrative and ulcerated mucinous adenocarcinoma that is poorly differentiated. The tumor extends to the subserosa, with 13 out of 18 examined lymph nodes showing metastasis. The surgical margins are uninvolved, and there is no specified evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment.

The pathology report indicates the presence of two nodules of invasive mammary carcinoma in the right breast, specifically infiltrating lobular carcinoma and infiltrating ductal carcinoma, both classified as Nottingham grade I. The lobular carcinoma has metastasized to one of the right axillary sentinel lymph nodes, while the ductal carcinoma shows no evidence of metastasis in the lymph nodes. Both tumors exhibit HER2/neu protein overexpression, but fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) testing reveals no amplification for HER2/neu.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated solid urothelial carcinoma with squamous differentiation, primarily located in the right trigone, exhibiting invasion through all parietal layers and into the perivesical fatty tissue. There are three tumor-free lymph nodes, and the deep resection margins, including the urethra, ureters, and vas deferens, are clear of tumor. The tumor classification is pT3b, pNO (0/9), L0, V0, R0, G2, with a maximum tumor size of 2.5 cm and foci of moderate dysplasia in the remaining bladder urothelium.

The pathology report indicates that the specimen consists of the uterus and left fallopian tube, revealing an invasive moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma measuring 3.4 x 3.0 cm, with infiltration into the stroma but not compromising the resection margins. Additionally, there is evidence of squamous cell carcinoma in situ, neoplastic lymphatic embolization, uterine leiomyomas, and endometriosis in the parametrium and left fallopian tube. The pathological staging is classified as pT1b1, pN1 according to the TNM 7th edition.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has been diagnosed with papillary thyroid carcinoma, with a focus identified in the left thyroid lobe and a larger tumor measuring 5.0 cm found in the total thyroidectomy specimen. The carcinoma has extended into extrathyroidal soft tissues and has metastasized to 10 out of 23 lymph nodes, with evidence of extracapsular extension. The report highlights the presence of a single focus of carcinoma adjacent to vessels and adipose tissue in the left thyroid lobe, suggesting a possible connection to the main tumor mass.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma in the right breast, classified as Nottingham grade 3, with a tumor size of 2.7 cm and negative surgical margins. The right axillary sentinel lymph node biopsy showed no evidence of neoplasm, with 0 out of 1 lymph node positive for cancer. Additional findings include atypical ductal hyperplasia, fibrocystic changes, and fat necrosis in the breast tissue, with the tumor being positive for estrogen and progesterone receptors and negative for HER-2/neu.

The pathology report indicates that the left axillary sentinel lymph nodes were negative for tumor involvement, with no cancer detected in two lymph nodes from the first and one from the second biopsy (0/3). The left breast simple mastectomy revealed an invasive ductal carcinoma measuring 7mm, classified as SBR grade III, arising in the context of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ with central necrosis, and the excisional margins were free of tumor. Additional findings included weak estrogen receptor expression in 30% of cells, no progesterone receptor expression, and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 10-20%, with HER2 status pending.

The pathology report confirms a diagnosis of poorly differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma in the right breast, measuring 7.5 cm and extending to the superior surgical margin. Ten regional lymph nodes were found to be positive for metastatic invasive ductal carcinoma, indicating advanced disease with a pathologic TNM stage of T3 N3 MX, stage IIIC. The remaining surgical margins, except for the superior margin, are free of tumor, and the skin and attached fibrofatty breast tissue are negative for malignancy.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive lobular carcinoma in the right breast, with two separate lesions measuring up to 7 cm and positive margins at the posterior margin (2 mm). Additionally, metastatic mammary carcinoma was found in two right axillary sentinel lymph nodes, with one node showing extranodal extension. The left breast tissue was reported as benign with fibrocystic changes, and no distant metastasis was noted.

The pathology report indicates that both sentinel lymph nodes from the right axilla are negative for tumor involvement based on histological examination. The right breast mastectomy reveals a well-differentiated infiltrating ductal carcinoma measuring 2.4 cm, with associated ductal carcinoma in situ and no evidence of lymphovascular or perineural invasion, and negative margins. The tumor is classified as AJCC stage pT2N0Mx, and the findings correlate with the pre-operative diagnosis of ruling out ductal carcinoma in situ.

The pathology report indicates the presence of papillary serous carcinoma in multiple sites, including the omentum, right ovary, left adnexa, and small bowel mesenteric implants, with significant tumor involvement and metastasis. The largest tumor measured 10 cm and showed lymphovascular space invasion, while the colonic margins of resection were negative for tumor. The overall staging is classified as pT3c, pNX, pMX, corresponding to FIGO stage IIIC.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme in the left frontal lobe biopsy, characterized by high-grade glioma that infiltrates normal brain tissue and shows extensive necrosis. The MIB-1 labeling index for the tumor is reported at 10%, suggesting a moderate level of cellular proliferation. Additionally, the second specimen reveals reactive gliosis in the white matter, with an increase in uniform reactive astrocytes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive moderately to poorly differentiated nonkeratinizing squamous cell carcinoma of the cervix, measuring 5.2 cm, with invasion into the endocervix and margins that are uninvolved by carcinoma. Lymphovascular invasion is present, but all examined lymph nodes (18 in total) are negative for metastatic carcinoma. Additional findings include a submucosal leiomyoma in the endometrium and benign conditions in the ovaries and fallopian tubes.

The pathology report indicates that the left neck specimen shows a mandibular gland with fibrosis and inflammation, and two lymph nodes without tumor involvement. The composite resection of the left mandible and base of the tongue reveals a poorly differentiated keratinizing squamous carcinoma of the tongue, measuring 1.5 cm in thickness, with lymphatic and vascular invasion, but the margins of the lesion are free of tumor. Additionally, a microscopic focus of atypical epithelial cells suggestive of squamous carcinoma was found at the anterior margin, while other margins and the medial pharyngeal wall showed no tumor presence.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, specifically the conventional (clear cell) type, with a tumor size of 3.5 cm and a Fuhrman Nuclear Grade of III/IV. The tumor is partially cystic, abuts the renal sinus, but shows no local invasion or renal vein invasion, and surgical margins are free of tumor. Additionally, the excised perihilar lymph node was found to contain benign fibroadipose tissue with no evidence of malignancy.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenosquamous carcinoma in the ascending colon, classified as grade G3, with evidence of ulceration and peritumorous inflammation. The tumor has infiltrated the parietal layers of the colon and extended into the pericolic fatty tissue, but no cancer was found in the examined lymph nodes (0/12). The resection margins and surrounding omental tissue are tumor-free, and the tumor staging is reported as pT3, pNO, MX, L1, R0.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma in the right breast, measuring 3.1 cm and poorly differentiated, with lymphovascular invasion and separate foci of ductal carcinoma in situ. The estrogen and progesterone receptor tests are negative, while HER-2/NEU is weakly positive (score 2+). All sentinel and non-sentinel lymph nodes examined are negative for tumor involvement, confirming no metastatic disease in the lymphatic system.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 55 mm, with lymphatic permeation but no evidence of blood vessel or perineural invasion. There are peribronchial lymph node metastases, and the tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin, although there is soft tissue extension near the hilar resection margin. The overall classification is T3N1MX, with further examination suggesting potential involvement of the mediastinal margin.

The pathology report indicates the presence of high-grade spindle cell sarcoma in the left groin and dedifferentiated liposarcoma in both the right and left groin, with tumors measuring 8.0 cm and 12.0 cm respectively, both extending to the margins of resection. Additionally, a low-grade well-differentiated liposarcoma was identified encasing lymph nodes in the left groin, with no malignant involvement in the 19 lymph nodes examined. Special stains were performed, showing positive results for smooth muscle actin and other markers, confirming the diagnosis of sarcoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme from excisional biopsies of the right frontal brain. Microscopic examination reveals a highly cellular neoplastic proliferation with anaplastic features, extensive necrosis, and microvascular thrombosis. The MIB-1 labeling index is noted to be 11%, suggesting a moderate level of cellular proliferation within the tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a brain tumor located in the right frontal parietal region, measuring 11.0 x 9.0 x 3.0 cm. Microscopic examination reveals infiltrating malignant glial cells with necrosis, vascular proliferation, and significant mitotic activity, consistent with a diagnosis of glioblastoma. The final diagnosis is confirmed as glioblastoma (WHO Grade IV).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive, moderately differentiated rectal carcinoma, classified as adenocarcinoma grade 2. The tumor has penetrated all layers of the rectal wall, categorized as pT3, and shows lymphovascular invasion (L1, v1). This suggests a more advanced stage of cancer with potential for spread beyond the primary site.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the floor of the mouth, with a tumor size of 6.0 cm in greatest dimension and lymphatic invasion present. Among the dissected lymph nodes, 1 of 10 from the right Level IIB and 2 of 10 from the right Level IIA were involved by metastatic squamous cell carcinoma, with capsular involvement noted in the latter. The anterior mucous margin was involved by neoplasia, while other margins and salivary glands were uninvolved by neoplasia.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated papillary serous adenocarcinoma in multiple specimens, including the omentum, transverse colon, right adnexa, small bowel, pelvic peritoneal mass, sigmoid and left adnexa, rectal mass, bladder, cul-de-sac mass, and spleen. The tumor shows extensive involvement of the adnexa and omentum, with focal invasion into the bowel muscularis propria and submucosa, as well as lymphovascular invasion. Clinical data suggest a significant tumor burden, with a CA125 level of 5000 and a history of ascites and pelvic mass.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma in the prostate, with extraprostatic extension and perineural invasion, while regional pelvic lymph nodes are negative for metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, there are two adenocarcinomas identified in the colon: one at the splenic flexure that has not invaded through the muscularis propria, and another in the rectosigmoid colon that has extended through the muscularis propria with one of 26 lymph nodes showing metastatic involvement. The appendix is reported as grossly unremarkable with no significant histopathologic findings.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic serous carcinoma in the peritoneum and omentum, with a diagnosis of serous adenocarcinoma in the uterus and cervix, classified as FIGO grade 3 and stage IVA. The tumor exhibits extensive myometrial invasion and lymphovascular space invasion, with adnexal involvement noted in both ovaries. Immunohistochemical analysis shows the tumor is estrogen receptor positive and weakly progesterone receptor positive, supporting a primary endometrial origin.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade invasive urothelial carcinoma in the bladder, measuring at least 3.5 cm, with extension into the perivesical fat but negative surgical margins. The prostate shows a Gleason score of 3+3 adenocarcinoma, confined to the left apex and right mid, involving 10% of the gland, with negative surgical margins and no evidence of angiolymphatic or extracapsular invasion. Additionally, lymph node excisions from both the right and left pelvic regions show no metastatic carcinoma, and the urethral margin biopsy reveals benign urothelium without tumor presence.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the right lobe of the liver, with a tumor size of 5.3 x 4.9 x 5.5 cm and well-differentiated histology. There is no evidence of satellite nodules, portal vein invasion, or bile duct invasion, although microvessel invasion is noted. The specimen also shows complete fibrous capsule formation and no surgical margin invasion, with a diagnosis of cirrhosis accompanying the HCC.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade urothelial carcinoma in the bladder, characterized by over 50% squamous differentiation and invasion into the muscularis propria, with positive lymphovascular invasion. The prostatic urethra shows benign findings, including chronic inflammation and reactive changes, along with benign prostatic glands and fibromuscular stroma. The gross examination reveals multiple irregular fragments of soft tissue from the bladder tumor and smaller fragments from the prostatic urethra.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 3.9 cm, with negative surgical margins and no evidence of metastatic disease in the examined lymph nodes. The lower lobe resection showed no malignancy, and all lymph nodes from levels 10, R4, and 7 also demonstrated no evidence of metastasis. Overall, the findings suggest localized lung cancer without regional or distant spread.

The pathology report indicates that multiple excised lymph nodes from the right paratracheal and thoracic regions are benign with no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. However, a lobectomy of the right upper lobe reveals a moderately to poorly differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma measuring 6.5 x 4.3 x 3 cm, with tumor infiltration up to but not within the visceral pleura and involvement of the bronchial margin. The final pathologic staging is pT2bN0M0, indicating stage IIA lung cancer with no regional or distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated sarcomatous cholangiocarcinoma from a right liver lobe lesion, measuring 8 x 5.5 x 6 cm, with a single tumor focus. The tumor is confined to the hepatic parenchyma with negative margins and evidence of perineural invasion, but no definitive lymphovascular invasion was identified. Pathologic staging is classified as pT1, with extensive tumor necrosis noted in the specimen.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive grade 3 cholangiocarcinoma in the liver and gallbladder, with a significant tumor mass measuring 10.0 x 9.4 x 7.0 cm that invades the gallbladder wall. The gallbladder mucosa exhibits cholesterolosis, but the surgical margins are negative for cancer. Additionally, biopsies from the omentum and peri-duodenal region show metastatic cholangiocarcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, measuring 7.0 cm, with a composition of 60% clear cells and 40% eosinophilic cells, classified as Fuhrman nuclear grade 3, and showing invasion into the renal sinus adipose tissue and renal pelvicalyceal system. The resection margins are free of tumor, and no tumor is present in the adrenal gland or the examined lymph nodes. Additionally, multifocal necrosis and hemorrhage are noted within the kidney parenchyma, but there is no invasion into the perinephric adipose tissue or renal vein.

The pathology report indicates the presence of oligodendroglial differentiation with noted mitotic activity. There is a focal proliferation rate of 20%. The diagnosis is anaplastic oligodendroglioma, classified as WHO grade III.

The pathology report indicates that the left and right pelvic lymph nodes are benign and negative for metastasis. The hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy specimen reveals a high-grade endometrial serous carcinoma (FIGO grade 3) with superficial invasion of the myometrium and no lymphovascular invasion or extrauterine extension. Additionally, the ovaries and fallopian tubes are histologically unremarkable, and pelvic washings show benign mesothelial and chronic inflammatory cells.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately to poorly differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma of the pancreas, measuring approximately 3.2 x 2.4 cm, with evidence of perineural invasion and metastasis to one of twelve peripancreatic lymph nodes. Additionally, the report notes metastatic pancreatic adenocarcinoma infiltrating the posterior cervical wall, along with benign findings such as atrophic endometrium and uterine leiomyoma. The surgical specimens included a near total pancreatectomy, splenectomy, and hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, with the pancreatic margins being negative for invasive carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma of the stomach, with the tumor invading the full thickness of the stomach wall and extending to the peritoneal surface. There are multiple lymph node metastases identified, with significant infiltration noted in several lymph nodes. The surgical margins are free of neoplastic lesions, suggesting complete resection of the primary tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma (type: conventional/clear cells) in the left kidney, measuring 4.5 cm, with a Fuhrman grade of 2 and evidence of soft tissue invasion through the renal capsule into the peri-renal connective tissue, but no tumor present in the renal artery, renal vein, or ureter. The resection margins are free of tumor, and the adjacent kidney parenchyma appears unremarkable. Additionally, the gallbladder shows chronic cholecystitis with cholelithiasis, but no tumor is present.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated papillary serous adenocarcinoma affecting both ovaries, with extensive metastatic involvement in the fallopian tubes, uterus, omentum, and appendix. The tumor is classified as FIGO stage IIIC, indicating macroscopic peritoneal metastasis beyond the true pelvis. Additional findings include complex atypical hyperplasia with metaplasia in the endometrium and the presence of leiomyomas in the myometrium, while the cervix shows no significant abnormalities.

The pathology report indicates that a specimen was sent to the Biospecimen Core Resource (BCR) from the NCH location. It requires the completion of the TCGA Missing Pathology Report Form due to the absence of a detailed pathology report. Additionally, it requests the tumor type, histology code, and site code for the sample, which are necessary for quality control and case diagnosis.

The pathology report indicates that two sentinel lymph nodes from the left breast show no evidence of tumor, while the left simple mastectomy reveals two areas of infiltrating ductal carcinoma, classified as grade 2, with the larger tumor measuring 2.7 cm and extensive low-grade ductal carcinoma in situ present. Surgical margins are clear of tumor, with the nearest invasive tumor margin being 0.5 cm away. Additionally, both estrogen and progesterone receptors are positive in 100% of the tumor cells, and there are no lymph node metastases detected.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a total thyroidectomy due to a right thyroid nodule, revealing multifocal papillary thyroid carcinoma with the largest tumor measuring 3.9 x 2.7 x 2.0 cm, along with two additional foci of papillary microcarcinoma. The tumor is well-differentiated, exhibits extensive capsular and lymphatic/vascular invasion, and infiltrates perithyroidal soft tissue, classified as pT3NxMx. A biopsy of the Delphian lymph node showed no tumor presence, confirming that the malignancy is confined to the thyroid.

The histopathological examination of a 17 cm segment of the sigmoid colon revealed a 4.3 x 0.6 cm cauliflower-shaped adenocarcinoma that infiltrates the intestinal wall and narrows the lumen, with clear excision margins. The tumor is classified as tubular adenocarcinoma (G2) and is staged as pT2, pNO, indicating it has not spread to lymph nodes. Reactive lymphadenitis was noted in the surrounding lymph nodes, but there was no neoplastic infiltration at the excision lines.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated invasive lobular carcinoma with a primary tumor diameter of 2.2 cm, accompanied by several satellite foci measuring up to 0.1 cm and focal in situ spread. The tumor classification is lobular carcinoma, grade II, classified as pT2N0(0/3;sn)LOVORO. This suggests that there is no regional lymph node involvement, as indicated by the N0 classification.

The pathology report indicates that there is no tumor present in the hard palate, buccal fat biopsy, salivary gland margin, maxillary sinus mucosa, inferior turbinate, and nasal cavity tissue. However, an invasive squamous cell carcinoma, grade 2, was identified in the partial maxillectomy and hemipalatectomy specimen, with a tumor thickness of 2.5 cm and evidence of perineural invasion. Additional tissue from the posterior wall of the maxilla is pending decalcification, and supplemental reports will follow for further evaluation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of seminoma testis (pT2 NXMX), characterized by an 8 cm tumor with irregular edges and a medium consistency. Histological examination reveals solid tumor areas with round and oval nuclei, moderate lymphocyte infiltration, and evidence of intratubular germ cell neoplasia. The tumor infiltrates the tunica albuginea and is present in several blood vessel lumens, but no involvement of the funiculus was detected.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of Grade 2 hepatocellular carcinoma in the right lobe of the liver, characterized by a multinodular mass measuring 7.5 x 5.8 x 5 cm, with clear surgical margins and no evidence of vascular invasion. The spleen and pericholedochal lymph node show no abnormalities, with the lymph node being benign, while the gallbladder exhibits chronic cholecystitis without stones. Immunohistochemical studies reveal that the neoplastic cells are negative for insulin.

The pathology report indicates the presence of multiple tumors in the right kidney, specifically six tumors diagnosed as renal cell carcinoma of the clear cell type, all with Fuhrman nuclear grade II. Additionally, there is one renal cyst identified among the specimens. The report notes that the patient has a clinical history of von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) syndrome, which is associated with the development of these tumors.

The pathology report indicates an excised skin tumor measuring 1.7 x 1.5 x 0.7 cm, characterized as an ulcerated and pigmented nodular melanoma. The tumor is classified as level IV by Clark's classification, with a depth of 7.0 mm. Additional details regarding lymph nodes, invasion, and margins were not specified in the report.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic high-grade Mullerian-derived papillary serous carcinoma involving multiple sites, including the omentum, anterior abdominal wall, pelvic region, liver, appendix, ovaries, uterus, and rectosigmoid colon, with extensive infiltration noted in various tissues. The report describes the tumor's characteristics, including high nuclear grade, architectural patterns, and associated necrosis and inflammation, while also noting that some specimens show no evidence of carcinoma in the mucosa or muscularis propria. Additionally, the patient's prior left breast carcinoma does not resemble the current findings, suggesting a new primary tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a 1.7 cm papillary thyroid carcinoma in the left thyroid lobe, with free margins and no evidence of carcinoma in the examined lymph nodes or other thyroid tissue. Additionally, chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis is noted in both the left thyroid lobe and the right lobe. The overall staging is pT1, with no regional lymph node involvement and no distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of anaplastic astrocytoma (WHO grade III) with a MIB-1 labeling index of 8.6%, suggesting a high proliferation rate. The tumor exhibits diffuse infiltration, with varying degrees of hypercellularity and atypia, and numerous mitotic figures are observed. Notably, there is no evidence of microvascular proliferation or necrosis in the examined sections.

The pathology report describes three specimens from breast surgeries: a left breast superficial margin re-excision, a right breast simple mastectomy, and a left breast simple mastectomy. The left breast re-excision shows fibroadipose tissue with no evidence of neoplasm, while the right breast mastectomy reveals fibrocystic disease without malignancy. The left breast mastectomy, however, shows moderately differentiated intraductal and infiltrating duct carcinoma, measuring 4.5 cm, with suspicious foci for lymphatic invasion, but the margins are free of neoplasm.

The pathology report indicates that the right maxillary sinus tissue shows no evidence of tumor, with a diagnosis of poorly differentiated squamous carcinoma noted at a depth of 6.0 mm, but without lymphatic invasion. Additional margins from the right inferior turbinate, cheek, soft palate, hard palate, and anterior gum all show squamous mucosa with no tumor present. The report includes fragments of bone and soft tissue from the right maxillary sinus, with an ulcerated mass observed but no bony erosion identified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade serous carcinoma (grade 3) involving both bilateral ovaries and fallopian tubes, with extensive deposits of serous carcinoma found in the omentum, pelvic tumor, and abdominal tumor specimens. The uterus shows benign findings, including a normal cervix and inactive endometrium, but there are reactive mesothelial foci suspicious for serous carcinoma. A right side lymph node is reported as benign and negative for malignancy, and the patient is BRCA1 positive.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of clear cell renal carcinoma from a partial nephrectomy, with a Fuhrman nuclear grade of 2 out of 4 and a tumor size of 3.8 cm, confined within the renal capsule and without evidence of angiolymphatic invasion. All surgical margins are free of tumor, and the non-neoplastic kidney tissue shows no significant abnormalities. Additionally, biopsies from deep margins and surrounding adipose tissue are unremarkable and negative for tumor.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder shows mild chronic cholecystitis without any calculi. A left renal mass was diagnosed as papillary renal cell carcinoma, nuclear grade 2, measuring 4.2 x 3.8 x 3 cm, with negative surgical margins and no evidence of necrosis or vascular invasion, classified as pT1b. Additionally, the umbilical hernia sac excised contained fibroadipose tissue with mild chronic inflammation and scarring.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma with discrete intraductal spread, measuring 1.9 cm in diameter. The tumor classification is noted as NOS, grade II, and is staged as pT1cN1aLOVORO. This suggests a localized cancer with some lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates that all three sentinel lymph nodes from the left axilla are negative for tumor involvement. The left breast mastectomy reveals multifocal invasive ductal carcinoma, grade II, with the largest tumor focus measuring 6.1 x 4.5 cm, and negative surgical margins. Additionally, the right breast skin specimen is unremarkable and also negative for tumor.

The pathology report indicates that a biopsy of the left paratracheal lymph node was benign, and parathyroid tissue was identified. A total thyroidectomy revealed a 5.0 cm papillary thyroid carcinoma confined to the thyroid, with one parathyroid lymph node also negative for tumor. The report confirms a history of thyroid cancer and includes representative sections of the thyroid tumor for further analysis.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive lobular carcinoma in the left breast, measuring 21 mm, with no lymphatic invasion and clear margins. In the right breast, a moderately differentiated intraductal carcinoma with lymphatic invasion was identified, along with metastatic carcinoma in one of fifteen axillary lymph nodes. Additional findings include a hemangioma in the skin of the breast and various benign breast conditions, with receptor status showing positive estrogen receptors and negative progesterone and HER2 receptors.

The pathology report indicates a moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma of the stomach (antrum) measuring 7.5 cm, with infiltration into the serosa and adjacent adipose tissue, and evidence of lymphatic and perineural invasion. Metastatic involvement is noted in all examined lymph nodes from the lesser curvature and greater omentum, with extracapsular extension, and there are multiple neoplastic nodules present. The distal surgical margin is affected by neoplasia, while the esophageal margin is uninvolved, leading to a pathological staging of pT4a.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately-differentiated keratinizing invasive squamous cell carcinoma located in the right lateral floor of the mouth, measuring 5.3 cm and invading the anterior mandible and subcutaneous soft tissue. All surgical margins are negative for tumor, with the closest margins being 0.5 cm away from the tumor. Additionally, all examined lymph nodes from various levels are negative for tumor involvement, and the tumor is staged as pT4a pNO.

The pathology report indicates a 5.5 cm well-differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma of the cervix, with bilateral disease and a pathological classification of T2, NOS. Eight lymph nodes were sampled, all of which were positive for cancer, while the right posterior vaginal margin was also positive for invasive squamous cell carcinoma. The sample was collected fresh frozen following surgical resection, with a diagnosis made 11 days post-procedure.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a left parieto-occipital lobe biopsy revealing an oligoastrocytoma classified as WHO grade II, characterized by predominantly oligodendroglial features and relatively uniform nuclei with sparse mitoses. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positivity for IDH1 and a MIB-1 labeling index of approximately 6%, with p53 staining observed in 20% of tumor cells. Additional fluorescence in situ hybridization for 1p19q is pending, and the case has been reviewed by the attending pathologist for final diagnosis confirmation.

The pathology report indicates that both the left and right pelvic lymph nodes are negative for tumor involvement, with two lymph nodes from the left and four from the right examined. The prostate specimen shows prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3 + 4 = 7, limited to the prostate and involving less than 10% of the tissue, with perineural invasion but no angiolymphatic invasion or extraprosthetic extension. Additionally, the left and right seminal vesicles and vas deferens are negative for tumor.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has malignant mesothelioma of the right pleura, confirmed as the epithelial type, with a maximum tumor thickness of 1.7 cm and evidence of invasion into surrounding structures, including the diaphragm and mediastinal fat. Out of 24 examined lymph nodes, four were positive for metastatic mesothelioma, and one of eight lymph nodes from a separate site was also positive for metastatic tumor. The overall pathologic staging is pT3, N2, indicating locally advanced disease with regional lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a right adrenalectomy and right nephrectomy, revealing an adrenal tumor weighing 172g and measuring 9 x 7 x 5 cm, diagnosed as adrenal cortical carcinoma with a Weiss score of 7. Additionally, a 0.7 cm nodule in the right kidney shows granulomatous and gigantic cells, raising the possibility of tuberculosis. There is no evidence of lymph node metastasis (0/10) or invasion of the renal artery, and chronic inflammatory changes were noted following a previous cholecystectomy.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3+3=6, located in multiple areas of the prostate, while the seminal vesicles show no evidence of tumor involvement. The tumor has a positive involvement of the capsule but no extraprostatic extension, and the surgical margins are negative for tumor. Additionally, there is positive perineural infiltration, but no lymph nodes were present for evaluation, and the overall staging is pT2cNXMX.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic adenocarcinoma in the omentum, consistent with a primary colonic source, and identifies an invasive moderately differentiated colorectal adenocarcinoma in the right colon with a histologic grade of 2. The tumor has invaded through the muscularis propria into the subserosa, with one regional lymph node showing metastasis out of 24 examined, while margins are negative but close to the tumor. Additionally, a liver mass showed no evidence of metastatic disease, and the hernia sac was found to be benign with no signs of malignancy.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive moderately-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the right tonsil, measuring 2.2 cm, with all resection margins negative for tumor. Additional excisions from the right neck revealed dense fibrous tissue with a foreign body giant cell reaction, benign fibroadipose tissue, and no significant histopathologic changes in the salivary gland and lymph nodes, all negative for tumor. The left tonsil and multiple lymph nodes from both sides of the neck were also negative for tumor, and the overall findings correspond to AJCC stage II (pT2, pNO).

The pathology report confirms the diagnosis of a right frontal lobe tumor identified as glioblastoma multiforme, grade IV, according to the WHO classification. Microscopic examination reveals a pleomorphic and infiltrative proliferation of astrocytic cells with features such as mitoses, endothelial proliferation, and necrosis, with strong positivity for GFAP and negativity for LCA in the tumor cells. The specimen consisted of multiple fragments of heterogeneous soft tissue, and the findings are consistent with a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme, grade IV.

The pathology report indicates a 3.5x3x3 cm ulcerated and invasive squamous cell carcinoma located in the abdominal esophagus, classified as Grade III and infiltrating the adventitia. Microscopic examination reveals moderate keratinization, enlarged nuclei with variability, and the presence of mitotic figures, along with invasion into surrounding fat tissue and lymphocyte infiltration in the stroma. Out of 20 examined lymph nodes, 6 show evidence of metastasis, while surgical margins are uninvolved and there is no indication of neo-adjuvant treatment.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the liver, characterized by a large tumor measuring 12.0 x 15.0 x 12.0 cm with evidence of necrosis, hemorrhage, and portal vein invasion. The tumor is moderately differentiated with a trabecular histologic type, and there is intrahepatic metastasis present, although the surgical margins are clear. Additionally, the gallbladder shows chronic cholecystitis, and a regional lymph node biopsy reveals reactive hyperplasia.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of multifocal papillary carcinoma, dominant follicular variant, measuring 2.2 cm in the right lobe of the thyroid, with a second smaller tumor measuring 0.1 cm also identified as a follicular variant papillary microcarcinoma. The tumor exhibits minimal capsular invasion, with no evidence of lymph-vascular or perineural invasion, and the margins are uninvolved by carcinoma. Overall, the findings suggest a low-risk papillary carcinoma with no regional lymph node metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that the bladder neck margin shows no evidence of malignancy. The prostate specimen reveals moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3+4=7, involving both lobes but confined to the organ without extraprostatic extension or seminal vesicle invasion. The margins are clear, and the pathologic staging is pT2c, indicating bilateral disease.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic squamous carcinoma in multiple lymph nodes from the right neck dissection, with three out of nine nodes involved and evidence of extranodal extension. Additionally, a total laryngectomy and right thyroidectomy revealed a moderately differentiated invasive squamous carcinoma measuring 4.5 cm, with cartilage invasion but no perineural or vascular invasion. Other lymph nodes from the left neck dissection were negative for tumor, and squamous mucosa samples from various sites were also negative for carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that a left adrenalectomy was performed on a female patient diagnosed with pheochromocytoma following cardiogenic shock. The specimen received was a 29.13 gram left adrenal gland with a 4.0 x 2.6 x 2.3 cm tan homogeneous nodule, showing no signs of hemorrhage or necrosis. The final diagnosis confirmed the presence of pheochromocytoma in the left adrenal gland.

The pathology report confirms a diagnosis of right lower lobe squamous cell carcinoma, which is moderately differentiated and unifocal, measuring 1.8 x 1.5 x 1.2 cm, with no evidence of visceral pleural or lymphovascular invasion. The excised lymph nodes from levels 9, 10, and 4 show reactive hyperplasia and are negative for malignancy. Additionally, two small subpleural fibrous nodules were identified, consistent with areas of scarring, and no metastatic carcinoma was found in the examined lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates that the excisional biopsy of the right temporal tumor is diagnosed as glioblastoma (WHO grade IV), characterized by moderate pleomorphism, frequent mitotic figures, vascular proliferation, and necrosis. The tumor cells are positive for p53, with a Ki-67 labeling index of approximately 40-50%, and the MGMT promoter is found to be methylated, suggesting potential benefit from alkylating agent therapy. Additional assays for EGFRVIII and further details on MGMT promoter methylation will be provided in subsequent addenda.

The pathology report describes a 5x3x2 cm malignant tumor located in the right breast, identified as medullary adenocarcinoma. Microscopic examination reveals a necrotic and invasive tumor with pleomorphic hyperchromatic nuclei and a desmoplastic stroma containing lymphocytes. The tumor is staged as pT2, with a distance of 3 mm from the invasive carcinoma to the closest deep resection margin.

The pathology report indicates that there is no evidence of neoplasia in the examined lymph nodes from both the right and left pelvic regions. A radical prostatectomy revealed invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 8, which is organ-confined and shows no extraprostatic extension, although perineural invasion is present. Additionally, benign prostatic hypertrophy and chronic prostatitis were noted, and all surgical margins were free of carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an anaplastic astrocytoma, grade III of IV, in the brain, characterized by a moderately pleomorphic and densely cellular proliferation of astrocytes with a proliferation index averaging 9.5%. Microscopic examination revealed few scattered mitoses, but no endothelial proliferation or necrosis was noted. The report confirms malignancy and includes findings from both frozen section analysis and immunohistochemistry studies.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an 8.0 x 7.0 x 4.0 cm papillary adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 22.0 x 15.0 x 7.0 cm overall. There is infiltration of the visceral pleura, and the tumor is classified as pT2, with no regional lymph node involvement (0/37) and an unknown distant metastasis status (pMx). The tumor is graded as G2, indicating moderate differentiation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade II, with a tumor size of 1.5 x 1.4 x 1.2 cm, and associated ductal carcinoma in situ comprising approximately 20% of the tumor. All resection margins and sentinel lymph nodes are free of tumor, indicating no evidence of metastatic disease. Immunohistochemical staining supports the findings from the histological examination.

The pathology report indicates that the patient, a female with von Hippel-Lindau disease, underwent excision of bilateral pheochromocytomas from both adrenal glands. The left adrenal gland contained a pheochromocytoma measuring 5.8 cm, while the right adrenal gland had a larger tumor measuring 6.0 cm, both confined to their respective glands. The report notes abnormal mitoses and marked nuclear pleomorphism in both tumors, with PASS scores of 5 for the left and 3 for the right.

The pathology report describes a brainstem tumor characterized by sheets of poorly cohesive, large atypical cells with prominent nuclei and numerous mitotic figures, consistent with diffuse large cell lymphoma of B-cell type. The neoplastic cells show immunoreactivity for CD45 and CD20, confirming their B-cell origin, while being negative for markers associated with glial cells and T-cells. The diagnosis indicates a brainstem tumor with features of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, highlighting an angiocentric growth pattern and areas of glial and fibrous scarring.

The pathology report indicates that the gallbladder and portal lymph node specimens are negative for malignancy, while the right liver specimen shows hepatocellular carcinoma measuring 7.3 x 6.0 x 5.8 cm, located 0.9 cm from the liver resection margin. Additionally, there are foreign body type reactions in numerous intrahepatic vessels, likely due to an embolic procedure, along with background liver changes including focal microsteatosis and portal lymphocytic inflammation. Clinical correlation is recommended to assess the inflammation's cause and the overall implications of the findings.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive undifferentiated carcinoma arising from moderately differentiated endometrial adenocarcinoma, endometrioid type, with significant invasion into the outer myometrium. There is evidence of lymphovascular space invasion, but no malignancy is found in the cervix, bilateral ovaries, or fallopian tubes. The tumor is classified as FIGO Stage IC, indicating it invades more than half of the myometrium.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast, with a Nottingham histologic score of 3, and a tumor size of 25 mm. Lymph-vascular invasion is present, and two out of eleven examined lymph nodes show metastatic carcinoma, with the largest deposit measuring 14.5 mm. The surgical margins are uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being 5.5 mm from the tumor, and a minute focus of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is also noted.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma at the gastroesophageal junction, measuring 12.70 cm, with ulceration and invasion into the mucosa, muscularis mucosae, submucosa, muscularis propria, and adjacent adipose tissue. Neural infiltration and sanguineous vascular invasion are noted, with one out of twenty-three lymph nodes showing metastatic involvement, while margins and other examined lymph nodes are free of neoplastic involvement. The pathological staging is classified as pT3 pN1, indicating significant local invasion and limited lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the left and right pelvic lymph nodes are negative for carcinoma, with no tumor identified in the examined lymph nodes. The prostate specimen shows adenocarcinoma involving multiple aspects of the prostate, with a Gleason score of 7 (3+4) and evidence of extraprostatic fat involvement, as well as a positive surgical margin at the left lateral base. Additional findings include benign prostatic hyperplasia and inflammation, with the pathological staging classified as T3a N0 Mx.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has invasive lobular carcinoma, grade 1, in the right breast, measuring 1.1 cm, with clear surgical margins. The axillary lymph nodes examined show no evidence of metastasis. The breast specimen included a spiculated nodule with central necrosis, but no superficial lesions were noted.

The liver needle biopsy reveals well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma, classified as Edmondson-Steiner grade 1 out of 4. Special stains showed no significant changes, but reticulin staining indicated disruption of the reticulin framework. The specimen consisted of three cores of pale tan liver tissue, and the entire sample was submitted for analysis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the stomach, specifically located in the fundus, with a tumor size of 8 x 7 x 1.5 cm. The cancer has extended to adjacent structures, including the lesser and greater omentum, and 5 out of 7 examined lymph nodes show evidence of metastasis. The surgical margins are uninvolved, and there is no specified evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment or additional pathologic findings.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, measuring 1.8 cm, with a Fuhrman nuclear grade of 2. The tumor is classified as pT1, limited to the kidney, but has a positive margin status (R1) as it extends focally to the renal parenchymal margin, with no lymphovascular invasion identified. The overall pathologic stage is I, and there is no evidence of regional lymph node involvement or distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a left frontal tumor diagnosed as glioblastoma, WHO grade IV, based on findings of marked pleomorphism, atypical mitoses, vascular proliferation, necrosis, and brain infiltration. Immunohistochemical analysis revealed weak p53 expression in 10-20% of tumor cells and a Ki-67 labeling index of approximately 40%. Multiple biopsy specimens were analyzed, confirming the diagnosis across different samples.

The pathology report indicates that multiple lymph nodes from various locations are negative for malignancy. However, a left upper lobe biopsy reveals an invasive moderately-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma measuring 4.0 cm, with no invasion into the overlying visceral pleura and a negative bronchial margin. Additionally, there is evidence of nonspecific pleuropulmonary fibrosis and pulmonary emphysema, but the lobar lymph nodes examined are also negative for malignancy, suggesting complete resection of the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of tubular adenocarcinoma of the stomach, classified as G3, pT3, pNO, with intestinal type according to the Lauren classification.
