The tumor also contains focal low-grade areas of sclerosing liposarcoma with myxoid changes, and microscopic examination shows that the tumor extends to the inked surface. The specimen was large, lobulated, and weighed 1.5 kg, with approximately 60% necrotic tissue and various characteristics noted in the gross description.

The pathology report indicates that the biopsy of tumor margins shows focal gliomatous infiltration, while the removal of the left intracranial tumor reveals an oligodendroglioma classified as WHO Grade II. The specimens included both tumor margins and left intracranial tissue, with the latter consisting of multiple soft tissue fragments. The intraoperative consultation confirmed the presence of a low-grade glioma in the blood cautery sample.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of multifocal lobular carcinoma with focal ductal features in the left breast, classified as Nottingham grade I, with two distinct tumor masses measuring 5.3 x 2.7 x 1.4 cm and 1.2 x 1.0 x 1.0 cm. There is no lymphovascular invasion, and the surgical margins are negative for tumor, with the closest margin being 0.8 cm away. However, multiple axillary lymph nodes show metastatic involvement, with focal extracapsular extension noted, and further testing for Her-2/NEU has been ordered.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic papillary thyroid carcinoma in multiple lymph nodes, with the largest metastatic focus measuring 0.9 cm and evidence of extranodal extension in some nodes. The total thyroidectomy revealed two foci of classical papillary carcinoma, measuring 2.8 cm in the right lobe and 1.5 cm in the left lobe, with vascular invasion and extrathyroidal extension noted. Additionally, benign lymph nodes were identified in the left neck, while metastatic disease was confirmed in the right paratracheal tissue and right level three and four lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated endometrioid adenocarcinoma (FIGO grade 2) in the endometrium, with tumor invasion into the outer half of the myometrial wall and focal lymphovascular space invasion. No tumor was found in the examined lymph nodes from both the right and left pelvic regions. The overall AJCC pathologic staging is pT1c pNO pMx, corresponding to FIGO stage IB.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma, Nottingham grade 3, in the left breast, with a tumor size of 2.3 x 2.2 x 2.0 cm and negative surgical margins. Additionally, metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in the left breast intramammary lymph node, while multiple left axillary sentinel and dissected lymph nodes were negative for tumor. HER-2/NEU testing has been ordered on the paraffin-embedded tissue.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrial serous carcinoma, with approximately 80% of the endometrial surface involved and 40% myometrial invasion, while the cervix is negative for tumor. All examined lymph nodes (16 total) are negative for malignancy, and both ovaries show benign serous cystadenomas without residual fallopian tubes. The tumor is classified as pathologic stage pT1a, with no evidence of lymph-vascular invasion or distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma in an ablated breast sample, with a tumor diameter of 10.5 cm and focal skin ulceration. A satellite node measuring 0.9 cm was also identified in the skin, while the dorsal resection margin is tumor-free. The tumor classification is NOS, G II, pT4b pN3a(11/22).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the ascending colon, with a tumor size of 4.0 cm by 5.4 cm and invasion into the subserosa. There is perineural invasion identified, but no vascular invasion or gross tumor perforation, and the surgical margins are free of tumor. The pathologic stage is classified as pT3, with 23 lymph nodes examined and no metastases detected.

The pathology report indicates that the left lymph nodes are reactive with no tumor seen, while the prostate gland shows adenocarcinoma primarily located in the peripheral zone, with a Gleason score of 7/10. The tumor has a dominant nodule measuring 1.1 cm and is staged at least pT2c, with positive margins noted at the right prostatic apex and very close to the bladder neck margin, although no carcinoma was identified in the bladder neck specimen. Perineural invasion is present, but there is no evidence of lymphatic invasion or extraprosthetic invasion, and further clinical correlation is recommended.

The pathology report indicates that the right frontal tumor is classified as a WHO Grade III mixed oligoastrocytoma, characterized by variable cellularity and pleomorphic nuclei, with a maximum mitotic count exceeding five per 10 high power fields. Immunohistochemical studies show no loss of 1p or 19q, and no EGFR amplification was detected. The findings suggest a diagnosis of anaplastic glioma, with the report highlighting the challenges in grading oligoastrocytomas due to the lack of a specific grading scheme.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive moderately differentiated pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma measuring 2.0 x 1.7 x 1.5 cm, which extends beyond the pancreas but does not involve major vascular structures or surgical margins. All examined regional lymph nodes (20) and a lymph node from the hepatic artery are negative for malignancy, suggesting no lymphatic spread. Additionally, the gallbladder shows no significant pathological changes.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma in the right breast, measuring 2.1 x 1.4 x 1.3 cm, with a Nottingham grade II and negative surgical margins. Additionally, a separate ductal carcinoma in situ nodule was found in the upper inner quadrant, while all seven right axillary sentinel lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The left breast shows mild proliferative changes with ductal hyperplasia without atypia, and further receptor analysis has been ordered.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma with hybrid oncocytic and focal papillary features in a right kidney partial nephrectomy specimen, with the largest tumor measuring 4.5 cm and confined to the kidney. Surgical margins are free of malignancy, and the pathologic stage is classified as pT1b NX MX. Immunohistochemical tests support the diagnosis, and there is no evidence of sarcomatoid features, perineural invasion, or lymphovascular invasion.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of oligodendroglioma, grade B, in a brain biopsy from the temporal lobe, with a MIB-1 labeling index of approximately 8%. The tumor is characterized by infiltrative growth, microcystic changes, and the presence of microgemistocytic cells, along with areas of nuclear atypia and mitotic figures. No vascular endothelial hyperplasia or necrosis was observed in the examined tissue.

The pathology report indicates the presence of endometrial adenocarcinoma, mixed endometrioid and serous types, FIGO grade 3, identified in a polypoid mass within the uterus, with invasion into the myometrium and additional sessile lesions also showing similar characteristics. All examined lymph nodes, including those from the right and left pelvic regions and para-aortic areas, are negative for tumor involvement, and the margins are clear of tumor. A benign endometrial polyp is noted, and the bilateral ovaries and fallopian tubes appear unremarkable.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of dedifferentiated liposarcoma in the left retroperitoneum, with a well-differentiated liposarcoma component, measuring 21.0 cm, and extending to the renal capsule but not involving the renal parenchyma or adrenal gland. The left kidney and adrenal gland were removed during a radical nephrectomy and adrenalectomy, and the resection margins were reported as uninvolved. Additionally, the spleen showed no significant pathological changes following splenectomy.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the stomach, with a tumor size of 16 cm and an exophytic growth pattern. The tumor invades the perigastric fat but shows no evidence of lymphatic or venous invasion, and all surgical margins are free of tumor. Additionally, none of the 15 examined lymph nodes show metastasis, and the omentum is hyperemic without signs of metastatic disease.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary carcinoma of the thyroid in the left lobe, measuring 1.5 cm, with extra-glandular extension and free margins of excision. Additionally, a follicular adenoma was identified in the right lobe of the thyroid, along with nodular goiter and chronic inflammation. The report also includes a specimen for the right inferior parathyroid gland, which showed no tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of clear cell carcinoma in the right ovary, classified as high-grade, and endometrial carcinoma with both endometrioid and clear cell features in the uterus, which is confined to the endometrium. Additional findings include benign conditions in the right fallopian tube and left adnexa, as well as negative results for metastatic carcinoma in multiple lymph nodes and omental biopsies. The report also notes the presence of acute inflammation and abscess formation in the umbilical hernia sac, but no malignancy was detected in that specimen.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of anaplastic oligodendroglioma located in the right frontal and temporal lobes of the brain. The tumor is classified as grade 3 and there is no evidence of metastasis or lymph node involvement. The patient is a Caucasian female, and no specific treatment details such as chemotherapy were provided.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of myxofibrosarcoma, a high-grade soft tissue tumor located in the right thigh, measuring 20 cm with deep fascial extension and a necrosis percentage of 15-20%. The tumor is classified as grade 3, with positive proximal margins and a close posterior margin, while lymphovascular invasion was not identified and two lymph nodes were negative for malignancy. The report highlights the presence of pleomorphic and storiform features, with some areas showing lower grade characteristics, and notes that the tumor is staged as pT2b according to AJCC criteria.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary carcinoma, follicular variant, with oncocytic features, arising in a parasitic nodule of the thyroid, measuring 5 cm in greatest diameter. The tumor is well-differentiated, shows mild to moderate mitotic activity, and is completely encapsulated with no evidence of capsular or blood vessel invasion, nor extrathyroid extension, and surgical margins are free of tumor. Additionally, a separate focus of papillary microcarcinoma measuring 0.35 cm is noted in the right lobe, along with findings of nodular hyperplasia and chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis in the non-neoplastic thyroid tissue.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated, multifocal, bilateral adenocarcinoma of the prostate, classified as pT2c with a maximum tumor diameter of 1.6 cm and a Gleason score of 4+3=7. The tumor is limited to the organ with no evidence of invasion into blood or lymph vessels, and both lymph nodes examined were tumor-free. Additional findings include prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia and myoglandular prostatic hyperplasia, with a tumor-free surgical margin.

The pathology report indicates the presence of moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in both the right upper lobe and right lower lobe of the lung, with the tumors measuring 2.1 cm and 6.6 cm in greatest diameter, respectively. The right upper lobe tumor shows no vascular or perineural invasion, while the lower lobe tumor involves the mainstem bronchus but has free margins. Additionally, multiple mediastinal lymph nodes were examined, all of which were found to be benign, with no evidence of metastatic disease.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of unifocal papillary carcinoma located in the left thyroid gland, with a tumor size of 0.7 x 0.7 x 0.7 cm. There is no evidence of extrathyroidal extension noted in the report. Additionally, no lymph nodes were examined during the evaluation.

The pathology report indicates that the left frontotemporal mass is diagnosed as anaplastic astrocytoma (WHO grade III), characterized by moderate to high cellularity, marked nuclear pleomorphism, and perineuronal satellitosis, with no vascular proliferation or necrosis observed. Immunostaining shows an increased nuclear labeling rate for MIB-1, supporting the diagnosis of anaplastic change, and many nuclei are positive for p53. Molecular studies for MGMT, IDH1, and 1p19q are currently in progress.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of low-grade oligoastrocytoma, astrocytic predominant (WHO grade II), in the left anterolateral temporal lobe. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positive GFAP staining in tumor cells, negative IDH1 (R132H), weak to moderate p53 expression, and low Ki67 labeling, supporting the diagnosis. The samples were received from multiple portions of the left anterior lateral temporal lobe and a collection sock, with representative sections submitted for further analysis.

The pathology report indicates the presence of Barrett's esophagus with low-grade and focal high-grade dysplasia, but no invasive carcinoma was found in that biopsy. However, a separate biopsy of a tumor in the esophagus confirmed the diagnosis of invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. Additional biopsies from the stomach and distal esophagus showed no tumors or significant pathological findings, with mild chronic inflammation noted in the stomach.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma following a right partial glossectomy. The tumor has a maximum depth of invasion of 0.8 cm, with the resection margins being free of tumor. No evidence of vascular, lymphatic, or perineural invasion was identified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated basaloid squamous cell carcinoma in the right pharynx, with a tumor size of 3.1 x 2.2 x 1.9 cm and evidence of invasion into the tonsil and skeletal muscle, along with venous invasion. Surgical margins are focally positive for carcinoma, with the deep margin and specific peripheral margins showing tumor extension within 1 mm. Additionally, metastatic carcinoma was identified in lymph nodes at levels 2 and 3, while no metastasis was found in level 4 lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates that there is no evidence of neoplasia in the excised lymph nodes from both the right (0/5) and left (0/12) pelvic regions. A radical prostatectomy revealed prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 3 + 4 = 7, involving both sides of the prostate, with extra-prostatic extension and bilateral seminal vesicle involvement, but all surgical margins are free of carcinoma. The tumor is classified as pT3b, with multifocal high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia and extensive perineural invasion noted, while no angiolymphatic invasion was identified.

The pathology report indicates the presence of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the antrum of the stomach, measuring 5.5 cm, with local invasion into the muscularis propria and evidence of neural and lymphatic invasion. Fourteen out of thirty-four examined lymph nodes are involved by neoplasia, while margins at the proximal, distal, and esophageal sites are uninvolved. Additionally, moderate chronic gastritis with focal intestinal metaplasia is noted in the adjacent mucosa.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a tumor-free lipomatous atrophic lymph node and a right hemicolectomy specimen revealing a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the cecum, with tumor-free resection margins and no regional lymph node metastases. Immunohistological analysis shows the tumor cells are positive for broad-spectrum cytokeratins and exhibit a dense lymphocytic stromal infiltrate, suggesting a poorly differentiated colorectal adenocarcinoma. The findings may indicate microsatellite instability, potentially associated with hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive lobular carcinoma in the left breast, measuring 3.8 cm, with associated lobular carcinoma in situ comprising approximately 5% of the tumor mass. The sentinel lymph node from the left axilla showed no evidence of tumor, and all margins from the lumpectomy were negative for invasive carcinoma. Additional findings include fibrocystic changes in non-neoplastic breast tissue and a favorable Ki-67 proliferation index of less than 10%.

The pathology report indicates that both sentinel lymph nodes from the left axilla are free of tumor. The left breast biopsy reveals invasive ductal carcinoma, modified Black's nuclear grade 3, measuring 1.2 cm, with no lymphatic or vascular invasion identified, and all surgical margins are free of tumor. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positive estrogen and progesterone receptors, negative HER-2/neu overexpression, and a high Ki-67 proliferation index.

The pathology report indicates that the excised lymph node from the left cervical neck is diagnosed with malignant lymphoma, specifically the diffuse large cell type (IWF G1). Additionally, bone marrow biopsies from both the right and left iliac crests show orderly hematopoiesis and are negative for lymphoma. Overall, the findings suggest a localized lymphoma in the cervical lymph node without evidence of bone marrow involvement.

The pathology report indicates the presence of two tumors in the right kidney, both diagnosed as renal cell carcinoma with features of papillary RCC type 1, exhibiting solid and clear cell areas. Tumor #1 measures 1.1 x 1.1 cm, while Tumor #2 measures 2.5 x 2.2 cm, with both specimens submitted for further analysis. A supplemental report may follow after discussion of the case.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a small focus of invasive lobular carcinoma (0.6 mm) at the edge of the excised right axillary breast tissue, with surrounding adipose tissue and rare benign acini. Additionally, two sentinel lymph nodes from the right axilla show micrometastasis, with one node having a single focus (0.6 mm) and the other exhibiting multiple foci (largest 1.5 mm), but no extranodal extension was noted. The right breast mastectomy revealed a unifocal invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 3.5 cm, classified as Stage IIB, with positive lymph nodes (2 out of 15) and focal positive margins.

The pathology report indicates that there is no tumor present in the left and right distal ureter margins, distal urethral margin, and pelvic lymph nodes examined. However, an invasive high-grade urothelial carcinoma was identified in the dome of the urinary bladder, measuring 2.5 cm, with a histologic grade of 3/3 and depth of invasion into the muscularis propria. Additionally, prostate adenocarcinoma was noted with a Gleason score of 3+4=7/10, but no extraprostatic extension or tumor at the margins was observed.

The pathology report indicates that the left breast specimen shows invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC), Nottingham grade 2, measuring 3.4 cm, with associated ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) and metastatic carcinoma found in seven of eight lymph nodes. The right breast specimen reveals ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) with atypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH), with margins being negative for carcinoma. Overall, the findings suggest a significant presence of malignancy in the left breast and lymph nodes, while the right breast shows early-stage changes without invasive carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma (early gastric cancer) located in the middle third of the stomach, with a tumor size of 3.8 x 2.5 x 2.0 cm and no evidence of serosal invasion. All examined lymph nodes (79 total) show no evidence of metastasis, and the margins from the proximal and distal resection are negative for tumor involvement. The pathological stage is classified as pT1bN0Mx according to the AJCC 7th edition.

The pathology report describes a 3x4x1.5 cm ulcerated tumor located in the antrum of the stomach, diagnosed as poorly differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma. Microscopic examination reveals infiltrating serosa with mildly stratified glands containing malignant epithelium and hyperchromatic nuclei. There is evidence of lymphatic invasion, but no metastasis was found in the examined lymph nodes.

The pathology report indicates that the left axillary sentinel lymph node and the left axillary contents show no evidence of metastasis, with 0 out of 1 and 0 out of 7 lymph nodes affected, respectively. The left breast simple mastectomy reveals an infiltrating ductal carcinoma, grade 3, measuring 3.2 cm, with negative surgical margins that are close (less than 2 mm). Additional findings include no vessel invasion or ductal carcinoma in situ, and the non-tumorous breast shows proliferative fibrocystic changes with intraductal papillomatosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of acinar adenocarcinoma of the prostate with a Gleason score of 4 + 3 = 7, involving both lobes of the prostate and demonstrating unilateral extra-prostatic extension on the left side. The tumor is present at the bladder base margin, but there is no invasion of the muscular wall of the seminal vesicle, and all examined pelvic lymph nodes are benign. Additional findings include high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia, basal cell hyperplasia, and atrophy, with focal extra-prostatic spread and margin positivity noted.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma of the larynx, measuring 2.5 x 2.2 x 1.9 cm, with tumor involvement in the left true vocal cord, ventricle, anterior commissure, and invasion through the thyroid cartilage, but with negative surgical margins. A total of 81 lymph nodes were examined from various levels of the neck, all of which were negative for carcinoma. Additional findings include subcutaneous tissue inflammation with abscess and keratinaceous debris.

The pathology report indicates a right total mastectomy revealing multiple invasive ductal carcinomas, with the largest measuring 1.3 cm and classified as Nottingham grade II. No metastatic carcinoma was found in the examined sentinel lymph nodes, and the surgical margins are negative for carcinoma. Additionally, ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) and lobular carcinoma in situ (LCIS) were identified, with the invasive tumor cells testing positive for estrogen and progesterone receptors and negative for HER-2.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a right temporal lobe tumor diagnosed as a mixed oligoastrocytoma, anaplastic (WHO grade III), characterized by extensive cellular infiltration, brisk mitotic activity, and a high proliferation index of approximately 75%. Molecular testing revealed no evidence of the EGFRvIII mutation, allelic loss on chromosome arms 1p and 19q, or methylation of the MGMT promoter. An addendum suggests the possibility of a high-grade oligoastrocytoma transitioning to glioblastoma, grade IV, and recommends clinical correlation for treatment considerations.

The biopsy of a right frontal brain mass reveals an anaplastic oligodendroglioma (WHO grade III), indicating a progression from a previously diagnosed WHO grade II glioma that is 1p19q codeleted. The neoplastic cells tested negative for the IDH1 (R132H) immunostain, and further findings will be reported in an addendum. The sample was received as an 8.5 x 4.3 x 2.7 cm portion of brain tissue, with multiple representative sections submitted for analysis.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma arising in Barrett's mucosa, with the tumor invading the submucosa but not extending through the muscularis propria. The surgical margins are negative for malignancy, and all examined lymph nodes are negative for metastasis. The TNM classification is T1 N0 Mx, indicating early-stage esophageal cancer.

The pathology report indicates that there is no evidence of neoplasia in the examined lymph nodes from both the right and left pelvic regions. A radical prostatectomy revealed invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4 + 3 = 7, involving both lobes of the prostate and showing established extracapsular extension, but less than 5% of the prostate volume is affected. All surgical margins and bilateral seminal vesicles are free of carcinoma, and extensive perineural invasion is noted, with a pathologic TNM stage of pT3a, pNO, and pMX.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly-differentiated endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a female patient, with the neoplasm measuring 8.5 cm and invading less than 50% of the myometrium, while showing angiolymphatic invasion. There is no evidence of carcinoma in the bilateral fallopian tubes and ovaries, and all examined lymph nodes (17 total) are negative for carcinoma. The surgical margins are clear of invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being 22 mm from the invasive tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium, with a tumor size of 3.7 x 2.7 x 1.5 cm and a maximum depth of myometrial invasion of 0.4 cm. The cervix, ovaries, and fallopian tubes are free of tumor, and all examined lymph nodes (totaling 38) are negative for carcinoma. The pathological stage is classified as pT1a pN0 pMX, reflecting the tumor's localized nature without lymphatic involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma based on biopsies from both the cervix and endometrium. Microscopic examination reveals large fragments of a high-grade papillary carcinoma with necrosis and inflammation, suggesting stromal invasion. It is challenging to determine whether the tumor is primarily cervical or endometrial, although it leans more towards an endometrial origin.

The pathology report indicates that the right portal lymph node was examined and found to have no tumor present. The resection of a right retroperitoneal mass revealed a diagnosis of paraganglioma, specifically an extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma, with the tumor being very close to the inked surface. Immunoperoxidase and in-situ hybridization tests were performed for diagnosis, and the laboratory is certified under CLIA for high complexity testing.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary carcinoma of the thyroid in the right lobe, measuring 1.5 cm, with the tumor confined to the thyroid gland and free margins. Additionally, metastatic papillary carcinoma was found in one of two perithyroidal lymph nodes. The total thyroidectomy specimen included the right lobe, isthmus, and left lobe, with the left lobe appearing unremarkable.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma of the pancreatic head, measuring 2.3 cm, with perineural invasion present and extending to the peripancreatic soft tissue. The margins from the bile duct, pancreatic neck, and retroperitoneal excisions are negative for carcinoma, while eight out of twenty-three lymph nodes show metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, there is a cystic component to the tumor, and the differential diagnosis includes possible colonization of a retention cyst or large duct by carcinoma versus intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN).

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of left kidney papillary renal cell carcinoma, type 2, with a largest tumor size of 4.5 cm and multifocality, including two additional type 1 tumors and ten tubulo-papillary adenomas. The tumor is confined to the renal parenchyma with no evidence of invasion into surrounding structures, and the largest lesion has a Fuhrman grade of 3 out of 4. Additionally, there are findings of chronic pyelonephritis and arteriolosclerosis in the nonneoplastic kidney tissue.

The pathology report indicates that a partial nephrectomy of a 2.4 cm renal mass in the left upper pole revealed a diagnosis of conventional (clear cell) renal cell carcinoma with a Fuhrman Nuclear Grade of II/IV. There is no evidence of local invasion or renal vein invasion, and the surgical margins are free of tumor. The tumor is staged as pT1, indicating it is confined to the kidney and measures less than 7.0 cm in greatest dimension.

The pathology report indicates the presence of malignant mesothelioma, predominantly of the epithelial type, with multiple tumor nodules in the right lung and diaphragm, measuring between 0.5 cm and 6.0 cm. Surgical margins from the resection are free of tumor, and there is no evidence of lymphatic or venous invasion. The tumor has been staged as pT2, pNX, pMX, and exhibits a tubulopapillary growth pattern with moderate differentiation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of grade 3 clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, characterized by a 6.0 x 4.5 x 4.0 cm mass that extends into the surrounding fat and contains a tumor thrombus in the renal vein. Additionally, metastatic grade 3 clear cell renal cell carcinoma is present in both the right retroperitoneal lymph node and the anterior vena cava lymph node. The surgical margins are negative, and a benign cyst is noted in the inferior pole of the kidney.

The pathology report indicates that both the right and left ovaries and fallopian tubes show benign serous cystadenofibromas with multiloculated cysts and papillary excrescences, while the uterine specimen reveals a FIGO grade III endometrial adenocarcinoma that invades the myometrium. Additionally, multiple pelvic and para-aortic lymph nodes on both sides are positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma, indicating the spread of the cancer. The gonadal vessels on both sides are negative for tumor involvement.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic squamous cell carcinoma in one of four lymph nodes from the right neck level I, while all other examined lymph nodes from various levels are negative for tumor involvement. Additionally, a moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma was identified in the anterior floor of the mouth, measuring 2.0 cm with perineural invasion, but with negative margins. The report concludes that the tumor is close to the anterior gingival mucosal margin, and further sections of bone are pending decalcification for additional evaluation.

The pathology report indicates that the left hypopharyngeal mass is diffusely involved by invasive moderately to poorly differentiated papillary squamous cell carcinoma. The submitted tissue consists of multiple fragments measuring 8.0 x 7.0 x 2.0 cm, with no clear surgical resection margins identified. The findings were reviewed by the attending pathologist, confirming the diagnosis.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a moderately differentiated invasive colonic adenocarcinoma measuring 6.5 cm, which has extended through the muscularis propria into the serosal adipose tissue, with no evidence of angiolymphatic invasion and all margins being free. The preoperative and postoperative diagnoses confirm colon cancer, and twelve pericolonic lymph nodes were examined with no signs of metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, an EGFR immunohistochemical stain was performed, which was negative, but further testing is pending due to potential interference from the staining process.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in the right tongue following a partial glossectomy, with a tumor size of 1.6 cm and a thickness of 9 mm. All examined margins and lymph nodes (25 total) were negative for malignancy, and perineural invasion was present. The tumor is classified as pT1 with no regional lymph node metastasis, and no distant metastasis was identified.

The pathology report indicates that the excised skin from the stomal site shows inflammatory changes without any tumor present. In the right neck lymph nodes, two out of twenty-five nodes tested positive for metastatic squamous cell carcinoma, with the largest metastasis measuring 0.5 cm, while no tumors were found in the left neck lymph nodes. A total laryngectomy revealed moderately to poorly differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma measuring 4.5 cm, with involvement of multiple structures and free surgical margins.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of a mixed germ cell tumor in the left testicle, comprising 50% seminoma, 45% mature teratoma, and 5% embryonal carcinoma, with a tumor size of 5.5 cm and unifocality. The tumor does not invade surrounding structures, including the epididymis, tunica vaginalis, spermatic cord, and paratesticular soft tissues, with negative surgical margins. The AJCC staging is pT1 pNx pMx, and further comprehensive review is recommended for final staging.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, conventional (clear cell) type, with a nuclear grade of III/IV, in a 9.5 cm tumor confined within the renal capsule following a radical nephrectomy of the right kidney. The tumor exhibits a solid growth pattern with areas of hemorrhage and necrosis, while all surgical margins are free of tumor. Additionally, five paracaval lymph nodes were examined and found to be benign, with no evidence of metastatic disease.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of left renal cell carcinoma (clear cell type) measuring 6.0 cm with 30% necrosis and a Fuhrman grade of 3/4, along with a microscopic implant of carcinoma in the perinephric adipose tissue. There is no extension into Gerota's fascia or evidence of angiolymphatic invasion, and one lymph node was found to be free of tumor. Additionally, bronchial washing showed suspicious cells for metastatic renal cell carcinoma, but definitive categorization requires further immunohistochemical confirmation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating ductal carcinoma in the right breast, measuring 2.5 cm, with a histologic grade of II/III and a moderately differentiated nuclear grade. A non-comedo intraductal carcinoma component is present, comprising less than 10% of the tumor, and no tumor is identified at the deep surgical margin. Additionally, two out of seventeen lymph nodes show positive findings for metastatic adenocarcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that the excised tumor from the stomach's antrum measures 8 x 7 x 2 cm and is diagnosed as poorly differentiated intestinal-type adenocarcinoma. All nine examined lymph nodes show positive metastasis, and the tumor has not invaded the margins. Additionally, the tumor is HER2/NEU-negative, and there is no specified evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment or other pathologic findings.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of multifocal papillary carcinoma of the thyroid, with tumor sizes measuring 2.1 cm in the right lobe, 2.6 cm in the isthmus, and 0.4 cm in the left lobe, accompanied by extrathyroidal extension but negative surgical margins and lymphovascular invasion. Additionally, metastatic papillary carcinoma was identified in one of four right paratracheal lymph nodes, while the left paratracheal lymph nodes showed no pathological diagnosis. The tumor staging is classified as T3, N1a, MX, and is categorized as Stage I for a patient under 45 years old.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of Grade 3 clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, characterized by an 8 x 6 cm mass located in the superior mid kidney with extension into perinephric fat. Coagulative tumor necrosis is noted, but the renal vein is free of involvement and surgical margins are negative. Additionally, no renal hilar lymph nodes or adrenal gland tissue are identified.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a glioblastoma, identified through an excisional biopsy of a 4.0 cm tumor in the left temporal lobe. The tumor exhibits features of anaplastic astrocytic proliferation, including microvascular proliferation, necrosis, and a proliferation index of 13%. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positivity for GFAP and a small fraction of neoplastic cells expressing mutant p53 protein, with no neuronal marker expression detected.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the right posterior section of the liver, characterized by a 7.5 x 6.6 x 5.1 cm encapsulated, multinodular mass with central necrosis, and a clear surgical resection margin. The tumor is classified as Edmondson-Steiner grade IV with focal capsular infiltration but shows no evidence of vascular or serosal invasion. The adrenal gland and gallbladder specimens show no tumor presence, with the gallbladder noted to be in a state of autolysis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, conventional (clear cell) type, with a Fuhrman Nuclear Grade of II/IV and a tumor size of 2.5 cm. There is no evidence of local invasion, renal vein invasion, or small vessel invasion, and the surgical margins are free of tumor with a clearance of 0.3 cm. The tumor is staged as pT1, indicating it is limited to the kidney.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of locally advanced, mixed adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, characterized by large-cell and clear-cell components, with mucin formation. The tumor is classified as pT3 pN2 pMX V1 R0, corresponding to stage IIIA, and has infiltrated the pericardial fatty tissue with evidence of lymph node metastases in the hilar region. However, the resection margins of the bronchus, vessels, and pericardial tissue, as well as certain lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The pathology report indicates the presence of moderately differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the left lobe of the liver, with two tumors measuring 3.4 cm and 0.9 cm, respectively. There is no evidence of satellite nodules, necrosis, or invasion of surrounding structures, and the surgical margins are free of tumor. Additionally, the liver shows signs of cirrhosis associated with hepatitis B virus (HBV).

The histopathological examination of the resected stomach reveals a grade 3 tubular adenocarcinoma that invades the full thickness of the stomach wall and has metastasized to multiple lymph nodes. The tumor shows significant infiltration into surrounding tissues, including vessels and perigastric fat, while the incision lines are free of neoplastic invasion. Immunohistochemical testing for HER2 shows a negative reaction in the invasive cancer cells.

The pathology report indicates the presence of infiltrating lobular carcinoma in both the right and left breasts, with Nottingham grade II tumors measuring 2.8 cm and 4.1 cm, respectively, and angiolymphatic invasion noted in the right breast. The right axillary sentinel lymph node is positive for metastatic carcinoma with extranodal extension, while the left axillary sentinel lymph nodes are negative for metastasis. All surgical resection margins are negative for tumor involvement, and additional lymph nodes from the right axillary dissection are also negative for metastatic carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has invasive high-grade urothelial carcinoma involving the bladder, with a significant lesion measuring 5 x 3 cm and invasion into the muscularis propria. Three out of nine right pelvic lymph nodes are positive for metastatic carcinoma, while all seven left pelvic lymph nodes show no evidence of tumor. The overall staging is pT2b, N2, MX, indicating advanced disease with lymphatic involvement.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of right renal cell carcinoma, papillary type, with a Furman grade of 3 and a tumor size of 11.8 cm, classified as pT2b. The tumor is unifocal and grossly confined to the kidney, with negative surgical margins of 2 mm for the renal parenchyma and less than 1 mm for the renal capsule. Additional findings include scattered sclerotic glomeruli and arterioles in the adjacent non-neoplastic kidney, with no evidence of sarcomatoid features or lymphatic invasion.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a population of CD20+ large B-cells amidst small B-lymphocytes, with features consistent with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL). Immunohistochemical analysis shows a proliferation fraction of 20-30%, and negative results for cyclin D1, CD138, CD30, and EBER, ruling out mantle cell lymphoma and plasmablastic lymphoma. The diagnosis is confirmed as diffuse aggressive lymphoma from the left neck lymph node incisional biopsies, with further workup pending.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an intermediate to poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring up to 5.5 cm, with evidence of tumor invasion into the pleura and surrounding tissues. There are multiple affected lymph nodes, and the tumor is associated with necrosis, inflammation, and signs of chronic pleuritis. The findings suggest a primary peripheral lung carcinoma that may have infiltrated nearby bronchi, with the possibility of a second focus of atypical squamous cell metaplasia in the fibrosing lung tissue.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive squamous carcinoma of the right oral tongue, with extensive perineural invasion and tumor present approximately 1.0 mm from the deep resection margin, while the lateral margin is free of tumor. Metastatic squamous carcinoma is identified in 2 of 4 left level II neck lymph nodes and in 1 of 7 level III lymph nodes, with extranodal extension to adipose tissue noted. The palatal and anterior mucosal margins show no tumor presence, and the remaining lymph nodes and right submandibular gland are negative for tumor.

The pathology report indicates an excised skin tumor measuring 2.5x2x1 cm, classified as melanoma with a moderately differentiated histologic grade. The report notes a Clark level III invasion, but does not specify details regarding satellite nodules, lymph nodes, or margins. Additional pathologic findings and evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment are also not provided.

The pathology report indicates the presence of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma in the axillary lymph node, with a tumor size of 1.4 cm. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positive reactions for CD 45 and CD 20, while other markers such as cytokeratin pan, melanosome, chromogranin A, CD 3, and CD 10 are negative. The tumor exhibits a Ki67 proliferation index of up to 40%, and there is no evidence of venous invasion or involvement of margins.

The pathology report indicates that the right adrenal gland specimen, obtained from an adrenalectomy, is diagnosed as a pheochromocytoma, a type of neuroendocrine tumor. The mass measures 5 x 4.5 x 3.5 cm and exhibits a largely hemorrhagic cut surface. Additionally, a portion of the right 12th rib was submitted, which consists of normal bone fragments.

The pathology report indicates the presence of metastatic non-small cell carcinoma in the anterior and hilar lymph nodes, with evidence of extranodal extension in the hilar node. The left upper lobe lobectomy revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma with a maximal tumor diameter of 10.2 cm, but the bronchial and chest wall margins were free of tumor. Additionally, multiple lymph nodes excised from various locations showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma, while some contained small sclerotic granulomata.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) with a tall cell variant, primarily located in the left lobe of the thyroid, measuring 5.2 cm and partially encapsulated, with no identified blood vessel invasion or tumor necrosis. Additionally, there is evidence of metastatic papillary carcinoma in a left paratracheal lymph node, measuring 0.5 cm, with a metastatic focus of 0.25 cm, and no extranodal extension observed. The surgical margins from the total thyroidectomy are free of tumor, and separate foci of papillary carcinoma, including follicular and microcarcinoma variants, are noted in the right lobe.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrial malignant mixed MÃ¼llerian tumor (MMMT) with invasion into the superficial myometrium, and no lymphovascular invasion was identified. Metastatic sarcoma was found in one right common iliac lymph node, while other lymph nodes and surrounding tissues showed no tumor presence. The tumor consists of mixed high-grade endometrioid and serous carcinoma components, with undifferentiated sarcomatous features.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of classical papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) in the right lobe of the thyroid, measuring 3.0 cm, with well-differentiated histologic grade and mild to moderate mitotic activity. Additionally, six papillary microcarcinomas were identified in both lobes and the isthmus, ranging from 0.08 to 0.6 cm in size, while the surgical margins were free of tumor. Parathyroid tissue was also noted, which was slightly hypercellular, but no blood vessel invasion or extrathyroid extension was observed.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma located in the liver, with a significant nodule measuring 12 cm. Immunohistochemical analysis shows positivity for CK7 and negativity for CK20 and TTF1, supporting the diagnosis of cholangiocarcinoma. Additionally, the liver tissue exhibits mild steatosis, chronic cholestasis, and mild to moderate fibrosis.

The pathology report indicates the presence of invasive squamous carcinoma in the right false cord and a grade 3 squamous carcinoma with lymphatic invasion in the laryngectomy specimen, affecting both supraglottic regions. The right thyroid lobectomy revealed multinodular goiter, while lymph nodes from the right parotid bulb and cervical regions showed no evidence of tumor. Margins of resection for the laryngectomy were free of tumor, with a tumor thickness of 1.2 cm noted.

The pathology report indicates that the distal left and right ureters are negative for neoplasm, while the additional prostatic tissue shows benign glandular tissue with squamous metaplasia but no invasive malignancy. A radical cystoprostatectomy reveals infiltrating high-grade urothelial carcinoma with squamous differentiation, measuring 5.5 cm, extending through the bladder muscular wall to the inked radial margin, and marked necrosis is present. Both left and right lymph node dissections are negative for malignancy, and the prostate and seminal vesicles are also negative for cancer.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 3.2 cm, with negative margins and evidence of vascular invasion. Five hilar lymph nodes and additional lymph nodes from levels 10, 5, and 7 were examined, all of which were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The tumor is classified as pT2a, indicating it is limited to the lung without regional lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a glioblastoma (WHO Grade IV) following a right parietal craniotomy for a malignant glioma, with evidence of extensive necrosis and microvascular proliferation in the tumor. Imaging shows a decrease in the enhancing lesion size, but there remains a heterogeneous focus of enhancement in the right parietal lobe, along with significant surrounding edema. Cytogenetic analysis reveals polysomy in several chromosomes, which may correlate with a poorer prognosis based on the number of abnormal markers present.

The pathology report indicates the excision of a 2 x 1.5 x 0.3 cm tumor located in the esophagus, diagnosed as moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. The tumor has invaded the muscularis propria, but all seven examined lymph nodes are negative for metastasis, and the surgical margins are uninvolved. There is no specified information regarding lymphatic or venous invasion, neo-adjuvant treatment, or additional pathologic findings.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of endometrial cancer, specifically a high-grade (G3) predominantly endometrioid carcinoma with some mucinous features, measuring 3.5 x 3.3 x 1.6 cm and invading more than half of the myometrium. All examined lymph nodes (16 total) were benign with no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. Additional findings include focal complex hyperplasia with atypia adjacent to the neoplasm and adenomyosis with leiomyomas in the myometrium, while other organs showed no pathological diagnosis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of Grade 2 clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the right kidney, characterized by a 6 x 6 x 3.5 cm mass located at the inferior pole, with no evidence of tumor involvement in the renal vein or collecting system. The surgical margins are negative, and no coagulative tumor necrosis is present. Additionally, multiple lymph nodes and soft tissue samples from the right adrenal hilar region are negative for malignancy.

The pathology report indicates that the left breast showed fibrocystic changes, columnar cell changes, sclerosing adenosis, pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia, and ductal epithelial hyperplasia, while the right breast revealed invasive lobular carcinoma with two foci measuring 3 cm and 4.2 cm, Nottingham grade 2/3, and lobular carcinoma in situ with comedo necrosis. The sentinel lymph node biopsy from the right axilla was negative for metastatic carcinoma, and surgical margins were free of invasive carcinoma, although the invasive component was noted to be less than 1 mm from the anterior margin. The tumor was ER/PR-positive and HER2-negative, with a total Nottingham score of 6, indicating a moderate level of differentiation.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade adrenocortical carcinoma measuring 17.1 cm, with significant capsular and vascular invasion, including invasion of the vena cava, and a necrosis rate of 75%. Surgical margins are reported as negative, but there is metastatic carcinoma found in one of two lymph nodes, and the tumor is classified as stage 4 (pT3 N1 M1). An incidental finding of a renomedullary interstitial cell tumor was also noted, while the resection of costochondral cartilage showed no lesions.

The pathology report indicates that the left lower lobe tumor is diagnosed as moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.3 x 3.0 x 2.7 cm, with no pleural or lymphovascular invasion. A total of 14 lymph nodes were examined from various locations, and none showed evidence of metastatic carcinoma (0/14). The pTNM staging is pT2 N0 Mx, indicating localized disease without lymph node involvement.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has poorly differentiated prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4+3=7, involving both the right and left sides of the prostate, with a maximum tumor size of 2.0 cm and approximately 8% of the prostate volume affected. The cancer is organ-confined with no evidence of extraprostatic extension, and all examined surgical margins and lymph nodes (13 total) are free of carcinoma. Additionally, multifocal perineural invasion is present, and high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia is noted.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma with a Nottingham score of 9/9, characterized by a tumor size of 5.5 cm and extensive intratumoral lymphocytic infiltration. There is also the presence of ductal carcinoma in situ, accounting for 25% of the tumor mass, and angiolymphatic invasion has been identified. Additionally, 10 out of 21 lymph nodes examined showed metastatic carcinoma, with one exhibiting extracapsular spread, and all hormone receptor tests (estrogen, progesterone, and HER-2/neu) returned negative results.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma, conventional (clear cell type), nuclear grade II/IV, in the left kidney, with a tumor measuring 2.1 cm that is confined within the renal capsule and shows no invasion of the renal vein. There is focal tumor necrosis and fat necrosis in the perinephric soft tissue, but all surgical margins are free of tumor. The non-neoplastic kidney tissue is unremarkable, and the specimen includes a segment of ureter and dilated proximal ureter.

The pathology report indicates a gastrectomy specimen from the cardia with an ulcerating tumor measuring 8 x 5 x 1 cm, diagnosed as poorly differentiated signet ring cell carcinoma. Out of 8 lymph nodes examined, 2 were positive for metastasis. The report does not specify the extent of invasion or the status of surgical margins, lymphatic, venous, or perineural invasion.

The histopathological examination of a resected sigmoid colon revealed a 7.5 x 5.5 x 3 cm tubulopapillary adenocarcinoma that infiltrates the entire thickness of the intestinal wall and surrounding tissues, with a minimum side margin of 0.1 cm. There is evidence of metastatic carcinoma in the lymph nodes, indicating advanced disease (Dukes C, Astler-Coller C2, pT4a, pNI). The intestinal ends are free of neoplastic lesions, but there is significant inflammatory invasion surrounding the tumor.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of infiltrating lobular carcinoma in the right breast, with a maximum tumor size estimated at approximately 5 cm and a Nottingham prognostic index score of 7, categorizing it as a grade II lesion. Metastatic carcinoma was identified in three out of seven lymph nodes, including the sentinel lymph node. Ancillary studies, including breast cancer marker studies, are pending to further evaluate the tumor characteristics.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in the right mandible, with a tumor size of 5.4 cm and a depth of invasion of 2.9 cm. Lymph-vascular and perineural invasion were identified, and two out of forty examined lymph nodes were positive for metastatic squamous cell carcinoma, with extranodal extension present. The surgical margins, particularly the proximal bone margin, were involved by invasive carcinoma, and moderate epithelial dysplasia was noted in several other margins.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a right upper lobectomy, revealing poorly differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma measuring 3.7 cm, with one of four examined peribronchial/hilar lymph nodes positive for carcinoma by direct extension. The remaining lymph nodes from stations 10, 11, 4, and 7 were negative for carcinoma. The tumor was staged as pT2a with lymphovascular invasion present, but all surgical margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that a wedge biopsy of the apical segment of the right lower lobe shows subpleural fibrosis and chronic inflammation, but is negative for malignancy. A lobectomy of the right upper lobe reveals poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma measuring 4.7 cm, with extensive infiltration into peribronchial lymph nodes, while several lymph nodes, including the right low paratracheal and interlobar nodes, are positive for metastatic squamous cell carcinoma. The bronchial and tracheal resection margins are negative for tumor, and the remaining lung parenchyma shows moderate to marked emphysematous changes.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive squamous cell carcinoma in the anterior floor of the mouth, with a tumor size of 3.8 cm and perineural invasion present, but margins are free of tumor. Additionally, one of seven lymph nodes from the left level 1 dissection shows metastatic squamous cell carcinoma, while no tumor was found in the right level 1 lymph nodes or in the left and right level 2-4 lymph nodes. Chronic sialadenitis and atrophy were noted in the submandibular glands, and ancillary studies are pending for further evaluation.

The pathology report indicates that the biopsies of the right and left pelvic lymph nodes, as well as the periprostatic fat and bladder neck margin, show no evidence of tumor. However, the prostate and seminal vesicles reveal multifocal prostatic adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 4+5=9, indicating aggressive cancer that invades the left seminal vesicle and shows extracapsular extension. The surgical margins are reported to be free of tumor, suggesting successful removal of cancerous tissue from those areas.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast, measuring 2.6 cm, with a Nottingham score of 8/9 and associated ductal carcinoma in situ comprising 5% of the tumor volume. Lymphovascular space involvement is noted, with two sentinel lymph nodes showing metastatic carcinoma, one with a size of 0.9 cm and the other with rare clusters of tumor cells. Surgical margins are free of lesions, and the tumor is positive for both estrogen and progesterone receptors.

The pathology report indicates that the anterior floor of the mouth shows invasive moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, with the resection margins free of tumor. Additionally, metastatic squamous cell carcinoma is present in 3 of 6 level I lymph nodes and 1 of 2 level III lymph nodes, while other examined lymph nodes and margins show no tumor. The report also notes benign findings in the gingival labial margin, mucosal tongue margin, and deep tongue margin, with no tumor detected in those areas.

The pathology report indicates that a right lung lower lobe superior segmentectomy and lateral basilar segment wedge resection revealed invasive poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, measuring 4.9 x 4.8 x 3.5 cm, with negative margins and no lymphovascular invasion. The excised lymph nodes (R12, R9, R4) were negative for neoplasm, and the pathological staging is classified as p stage IB (T2a N0 Mx). An addendum report is pending regarding visceral pleural invasion.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of metastatic adenocarcinoma with an acinar pattern, confirmed through multiple biopsies from the pleura and lymph nodes, with a primary tumor located in the right upper and middle lobes of the lung. The EGFR mutation analysis revealed a positive result for the E746 A750del5 mutation in Exon 19, which is associated with a higher likelihood of response to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. Additionally, the KRAS mutation analysis showed no mutations, suggesting a potentially better prognosis and responsiveness to targeted therapies in this patient.

The pathology report indicates the presence of an ulcerated, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colorectal type in resected colon material, located 3 cm from the resection margin. The tumor has infiltrated the pericolic fatty tissue and shows circumscribed penetration of the serosa, with 23 local lymph node metastases identified. The tumor classification is pT4, pN2 (23/29), pMX; G3, L1, V1, R1, with tumor-free resection margins.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated grade 3 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium, with tumor extent greater than half of the myometrium. The specimen was obtained from a hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, and the tumor size is reported as 0 x 0 x 0 cm. The surgical margins are uninvolved, and there is no evidence of venous invasion, although lymphatic invasion and lymph node involvement are not specified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated endometrioid adenocarcinoma with squamous differentiation, classified as Grade III, from a 5 cm posterior endometrial mass in the uterus. There is evidence of metastatic adenocarcinoma of endometrial origin in the bladder flap, with one lymph node sampled showing positivity among twelve nodes examined. The tumor is staged as T4, N1, and M0, indicating advanced local disease with lymphatic involvement but no distant metastasis.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive mucinous carcinoma, Nottingham grade 1, with a tumor size of 1.7 cm located in the subareolar region of the left breast. The surgical margins are negative, with the invasive carcinoma at least 3.5 cm from all margins, and no lymphovascular invasion or tumor identified in the examined lymph nodes. Additionally, there is focal atypical ductal hyperplasia and benign findings in the surrounding breast tissue and skin.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has a diagnosis of ductal adenocarcinoma of the pancreas, with the tumor measuring 4.0 cm and showing moderately differentiated histology (G2). The tumor extends beyond the pancreas (pT3) and has metastasized to 2 out of 14 examined regional lymph nodes (pN1). Additionally, carcinoma is present at the pancreatic margin, while other specimens, including lymph nodes and bile duct margins, are negative for malignancy.

The pathology report indicates that the left frontal tumor is diagnosed as an anaplastic oligodendroglioma, classified as WHO Grade III, with varying cellularity and infiltration into the cortex. The tumor comprises 70% of the tissue in the left frontal tumor specimen and 50% in the posterior margin specimen, with chromosome studies revealing losses on chromosomes 1p and 19q. Additional immunostaining for the astrocytic marker p53 was negative, supporting the diagnosis of oligodendroglioma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of intermediate-grade leiomyosarcoma measuring 7.6 cm, involving both the gastric mucosa and serosa, with a mitotic count of up to 21 per 10 high power fields and no tumor necrosis identified. The tumor is located 2.3 cm from the nearest resection margin, which is negative for tumor involvement, and a fundic gland polyp is also noted. The findings are consistent with the patient's clinical history of gastric leiomyosarcoma and the surgical procedure performed was a partial gastrectomy due to bleeding.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of poorly differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma (G-3) with a tumor size of 5x4.5 cm, which has invaded the perigastric fat tissue. Out of fifteen examined lymph nodes, one showed evidence of metastasis, while there was no venous invasion noted and the surgical margins were uninvolved. The tumor is ulcerated and located in the fundus of the stomach, with no additional treatment effects or significant findings reported.

The pathology report indicates that the patient has high-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma of the bladder, with multifocal tumor distribution and invasion into the lamina propria and inner muscularis propria, measuring up to 8.5 cm. All examined lymph nodes (28 total) were negative for tumor, and there were no tumors found in the prostate, seminal vesicles, vas deferens, or distal right ureter. The report also notes focal chronic and granulomatous inflammation consistent with treatment effects.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of advanced mucinous carcinoma (Grade 3) that has infiltrated the surrounding fatty connective tissue and has an inflammatory connection to the uterus. The uterus itself appears normal for the patient's age, and there are no affected lymph nodes (pN0). Tumor classification details include pT3, L1, V1, and a total of 30 lymph nodes examined with no metastasis.

The pathology report indicates that the left axillary contents contain 23 lymph nodes, all positive for metastatic carcinoma, with the largest node measuring 3.7 cm and exhibiting extranodal extension. The left breast excisional biopsy reveals a unifocal invasive mammary carcinoma measuring 2.8 cm, classified as nuclear grade III and histologic grade II, with associated ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) and lymphovascular invasion present. Additionally, a reexcision of the left breast deep margin shows a 2 mm focus of residual invasive carcinoma, with the final deep margin being negative for tumor.

The pathology report confirms a diagnosis of glioblastoma multiforme (WHO grade IV) in the left temporal primary tumor. Microscopic examination reveals pleomorphic glial cells, mitotic figures, tumor necrosis, and positive immunohistochemical staining for glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP), with a proliferation index of approximately 25% as indicated by Ki67 staining. The report includes both frozen and permanent sections of the tumor, supporting the diagnosis.

The histopathological examination of a total organ resection of the colon and rectum revealed a 6 cm cauliflower-shaped ulcerous tumor consistent with tubular adenocarcinoma (G2) that infiltrated the surrounding adipose tissue. The tumor was located at the rectosigmoid junction, with clear margins at the excision lines, but there were metastases identified in one of the lymph nodes. The final diagnosis is tubular adenocarcinoma of the colon with lymph node metastasis, classified as Dukes C and Astler-Coller C2, pT3, pN1.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of clear cell renal cell carcinoma in the left kidney, characterized by two separate nodules measuring 4.7 cm and 1.0 cm, with a Fuhrman nuclear grade of 2, and the tumor is confined to the kidney with negative margins. Additionally, there is an incidental finding of a papillary adenoma and evidence of immune complex-mediated glomerulonephritis, suggesting a membranous pattern of glomerular injury. Cytogenetic analysis revealed a loss of one chromosome 8, which is not specifically associated with any particular tumor type.

The cervical biopsy reveals invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, consistent with the patient's history of cervical cancer. Additionally, consult slides show both invasive and in situ endocervical adenocarcinoma with mucinous features, characterized by specific histological patterns and immunohistochemical markers. The endometrial curettings are negative for malignancy, indicating no evidence of cancer in that tissue.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of papillary renal cell carcinoma (Fuhrman nuclear grade 2) in the left kidney, with a multifocal tumor measuring 2.5 cm and a positive surgical margin at the cauterized parenchymal margin, classified as pathologic stage I. Additionally, the report describes prostatic adenocarcinoma (Gleason score 3 + 4 = 7) involving both lobes of the prostate, with extraprostatic extension and a positive surgical margin at the left bladder neck, classified as pathologic stage III. No lymphovascular invasion was identified in either tumor, and regional lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates that the peritoneal and small bowel implants are both positive for adenocarcinoma, while the sigmoid colon shows a moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma with full muscle wall thickness invasion and metastasis to one of twenty-five lymph nodes. The tumor measures 5 x 3.5 x 1.6 cm and has negative margins, indicating complete resection, although there are tumor implants present in the pericolic fat. The rectal and colon donut specimens are negative for tumor, and additional findings include a tubular adenoma associated with the carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of conventional clear cell renal cell carcinoma with sarcomatoid features (10%) from a right partial nephrectomy specimen, measuring 3.2 cm in greatest diameter. The tumor is classified as Fuhrman Nuclear Grade III/IV, with no local invasion or renal vein invasion identified, and the surgical margins are free of tumor. The tumor is staged as pT1, indicating it is confined to the kidney and measures less than 7.0 cm.

The pathology report indicates that biopsies of the right upper and left lower parathyroid glands showed no pathological diagnosis, while the left paratracheal lymph node biopsy revealed follicular nodular disease. A total thyroidectomy specimen demonstrated multifocal papillary carcinoma, with a dominant tumor measuring 2.6 cm in the right lobe and a microcarcinoma in the left lobe. The report confirms that the tumor margins are uninvolved by carcinoma, with no evidence of lymph-vascular or perineural invasion, and no regional lymph node metastasis was identified.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of high-grade pleomorphic leiomyosarcoma in a right buttock mass measuring 8.0 cm, with involvement of superficial soft tissue and focal extension to underlying skeletal muscle, as well as ulceration of the skin surface. Multiple satellite nodules were observed adjacent to the main mass, but the resection margins were uninvolved, with the closest deep margin showing a clearance of 0.1 cm. Additional specimens from the new inferior medial margin and superior margin were negative for malignancy, although microscopic nodules of leiomyosarcoma were noted at the superior margin extending to the cauterized and inked margin.

The pathology report indicates that the patient underwent a total thyroidectomy due to a left thyroid nodule, which was found to be a well-encapsulated papillary thyroid carcinoma. Additionally, two lymph nodes from the left level VI were excised and found to be positive for metastatic carcinoma consistent with papillary thyroid carcinoma. The thyroid tissue also showed a background of lymphocytic thyroiditis, and the carcinoma was noted to be closely approaching the inked margin.

The pathology report indicates a diagnosis of invasive lobular carcinoma of the right breast, characterized as pleomorphic with focal signet cells, and a Nottingham grade of II. The tumor measures 2.5 cm and is associated with lobular carcinoma in situ, with two out of eleven lymph nodes positive for carcinoma. The invasive tumor cells are positive for estrogen and progesterone receptors and negative for HER2/NEU, with negative surgical margins for both in situ and invasive carcinoma.

The pathology report indicates the presence of a moderately differentiated colorectal adenocarcinoma in the resected colon and rectosigmoid, characterized by ulceration and invasive spread into the intestinal wall and surrounding fatty tissue, with a minimum distance of 2 mm to the soft tissue resection margin. The excised soft tissue from the abdominal wall shows fibrosis and chronic granulating inflammation, but no evidence of rectal carcinoma. All examined periproctic and mesocolic lymph nodes are free of tumor, leading to a final tumor stage classification of pT3, pNo (0/38), LO V0; G2.

The pathology report indicates that the left eye enucleation specimen reveals a malignant melanoma of mixed cell type, with involvement of the ciliary body but no extrascleral extension. The tumor measures 1.4 x 1.3 x 0.9 cm and shows a mitotic rate of 6 mitoses per 10 high power fields, with light pigmentation and scattered intratumoral lymphocytes. Pathologic staging is classified as pT3b due to ciliary body involvement, and there is no evidence of vascular invasion or involvement of regional lymph nodes.
